{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780729425983,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbeb037001Vi25oe995z4Dnb","messageID":"msg_e9bbeaa50001P4eN3xa8y6ig7F","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","snapshot":"3124c08842e7bf74cd97349ab4baa7470155e88e","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729435808,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_tn1XziyTjPKg5APzU6VIgTuc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","offset":1,"limit":180},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n2: \n3: ``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\n4: it via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n5: \n6: CAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\n7: mutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\n8: created up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\n9: pool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\n10: the AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\n11: enqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\n12: batches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n13: \n14: The synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n15: (early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n16: ``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\n17: behaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\n18: events; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\n19: without a redeploy.\n20: \"\"\"\n21: \n22: from __future__ import annotations\n23: \n24: from uuid import UUID\n25: \n26: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n27: \n28: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n29: from core_api.services.audit_queue import get_audit_queue\n30: \n31: \n32: async def log_action(\n33:     db: AsyncSession,\n34:     *,\n35:     tenant_id: str,\n36:     agent_id: str | None = None,\n37:     action: str,\n38:     resource_type: str,\n39:     resource_id: UUID | None = None,\n40:     detail: dict | None = None,\n41: ) -> None:\n42:     \"\"\"Record an audit event. Async-batched via queue when available;\n43:     falls through to a synchronous POST otherwise.\n44: \n45:     ``db`` is unused (audit persistence is owned by the storage layer)\n46:     but kept in the signature for back-compat with the ``ServiceHooks``\n47:     contract — callers pass it through; switching them all to drop the\n48:     arg is a separate, scoped change.\n49:     \"\"\"\n50:     payload = {\n51:         \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n52:         \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n53:         \"action\": action,\n54:         \"resource_type\": resource_type,\n55:         \"resource_id\": str(resource_id) if resource_id else None,\n56:         \"detail\": detail,\n57:     }\n58:     queue = get_audit_queue()\n59:     if queue is not None:\n60:         # Non-blocking enqueue. Overflow is mapped to a structured\n61:         # warning + drop counter inside the queue — the request hot\n62:         # path stays fast even when storage-api is degraded.\n63:         queue.enqueue(payload)\n64:         return\n65: \n66:     # Fallback: synchronous POST. Same shape as pre-CAURA-628.\n67:     sc = get_storage_client()\n68:     await sc.create_audit_log(payload)\n69: \n70: \n71: async def log_cross_tenant_read(\n72:     db: AsyncSession,\n73:     *,\n74:     home_tenant_id: str | None,\n75:     home_agent_id: str | None,\n76:     source_tenants: list[str],\n77:     surface: str,\n78:     result_count_by_tenant: dict[str, int] | None = None,\n79:     query_summary: str | None = None,\n80: ) -> None:\n81:     \"\"\"Emit a ``cross_tenant_read`` audit event per source tenant touched.\n82: \n83:     Called from read handlers after they widen their query via\n84:     ``readable_tenant_ids``. The event is logged TO each source tenant\n85:     (``tenant_id=src``) so per-tenant audit-log queries surface \"who\n86:     read FROM my tenant\" — including the home tenant_id and agent_id\n87:     of the caller in ``detail`` for forensic traceability.\n88: \n89:     No-op when ``source_tenants`` is empty (single-tenant reads).\n90:     Emission is via the same async queue ``log_action`` uses — overflow\n91:     handling and back-pressure are identical.\n92: \n93:     Hook for ``AuthContext.source_tenants_for_audit()`` — callers pass\n94:     that method's return value as ``source_tenants``.\n95:     \"\"\"\n96:     if not source_tenants:\n97:         return\n98:     for src in source_tenants:\n99:         await log_action(\n100:             db,\n101:             tenant_id=src,\n102:             agent_id=home_agent_id,\n103:             action=\"cross_tenant_read\",\n104:             resource_type=surface,\n105:             detail={\n106:                 \"home_tenant_id\": home_tenant_id,\n107:                 \"home_agent_id\": home_agent_id,\n108:                 \"result_count_from_this_tenant\": ((result_count_by_tenant or {}).get(src)),\n109:                 \"query_summary\": query_summary,\n110:             },\n111:         )\n\n(End of file - total 111 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n\n``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\nit via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n\nCAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\nmutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\ncreated up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\npool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\nthe AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\nenqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\nbatches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n\nThe synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n(early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\nbehaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\nevents; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\nwithout a redeploy.\n\"\"\"","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Audit-event ingestion entrypoint.\n\n``log_action`` is the only public surface — every memory mutation calls\nit via the configured ``ServiceHooks`` (see ``core_api.app.lifespan``).\n\nCAURA-628 (2026-04-29): the legacy shape POSTed one audit event per\nmutation directly to ``core-storage-api``. Under bulk storms that\ncreated up to N HTTP-POSTs-per-bulk-create on the storage-api connection\npool + serialised tenant B's audit traffic behind tenant A's storm at\nthe AlloyDB ``audit_log`` table-level write lock. ``log_action`` now\nenqueues into a process-local ``AuditEventQueue``; a background flusher\nbatches events and writes them via ``POST /audit-logs/bulk``.\n\nThe synchronous-POST fallback path runs when the queue is not active\n(early startup, tests that didn't wire it, intentional kill-switch via\n``set_audit_queue(None)``). That fallback preserves the legacy\nbehaviour byte-for-byte so a queue-side bug can't silently drop audit\nevents; an operator can fall back to the legacy path during an incident\nwithout a redeploy.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom uuid import UUID\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.services.audit_queue import get_audit_queue\n\n\nasync def log_action(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    *,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str | None = None,\n    action: str,\n    resource_type: str,\n    resource_id: UUID | None = None,\n    detail: dict | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Record an audit event. Async-batched via queue when available;\n    falls through to a synchronous POST otherwise.\n\n    ``db`` is unused (audit persistence is owned by the storage layer)\n    but kept in the signature for back-compat with the ``ServiceHooks``\n    contract — callers pass it through; switching them all to drop the\n    arg is a separate, scoped change.\n    \"\"\"\n    payload = {\n        \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n        \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n        \"action\": action,\n        \"resource_type\": resource_type,\n        \"resource_id\": str(resource_id) if resource_id else None,\n        \"detail\": detail,\n    }\n    queue = get_audit_queue()\n    if queue is not None:\n        # Non-blocking enqueue. Overflow is mapped to a structured\n        # warning + drop counter inside the queue — the request hot\n        # path stays fast even when storage-api is degraded.\n        queue.enqueue(payload)\n        return\n\n    # Fallback: synchronous POST. Same shape as pre-CAURA-628.\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    await sc.create_audit_log(payload)\n\n\nasync def log_cross_tenant_read(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    *,\n    home_tenant_id: str | None,\n    home_agent_id: str | None,\n    source_tenants: list[str],\n    surface: str,\n    result_count_by_tenant: dict[str, int] | None = None,\n    query_summary: str | None = None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Emit a ``cross_tenant_read`` audit event per source tenant touched.\n\n    Called from read handlers after they widen their query via\n    ``readable_tenant_ids``. The event is logged TO each source tenant\n    (``tenant_id=src``) so per-tenant audit-log queries surface \"who\n    read FROM my tenant\" — including the home tenant_id and agent_id\n    of the caller in ``detail`` for forensic traceability.\n\n    No-op when ``source_tenants`` is empty (single-tenant reads).\n    Emission is via the same async queue ``log_action`` uses — overflow\n    handling and back-pressure are identical.\n\n    Hook for ``AuthContext.source_tenants_for_audit()`` — callers pass\n    that method's return value as ``source_tenants``.\n    \"\"\"\n    if not source_tenants:\n        return\n    for src in source_tenants:\n        await log_action(\n            db,\n            tenant_id=src,\n            agent_id=home_agent_id,\n            action=\"cross_tenant_read\",\n            resource_type=surface,\n            detail={\n                \"home_tenant_id\": home_tenant_id,\n                \"home_agent_id\": home_agent_id,\n                \"result_count_from_this_tenant\": ((result_count_by_tenant or {}).get(src)),\n                \"query_summary\": query_summary,\n            },\n        )","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":111,"totalLines":111,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py","time":{"start":1780729435801,"end":1780729435806}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e3c0905864be40a016a23c65bc69c8191845b82027013da06"}},"id":"prt_e9bbed692001754GHPGTYhr1XO","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbeaa50001P4eN3xa8y6ig7F"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729435856,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_vzCLZYLc59KBoTjdcd1AbooP","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","offset":1,"limit":170},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n2: \n3: Shared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\n4: under ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\n5: reaching into each other's private symbols.\n6: \n7: ``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n8: ``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\n9: for the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\n10: id\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\n11: string. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\n12: the MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\n13: strips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\n14: an ``HTTPException``.\n15: \n16: When the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\n17: to ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\n18: permission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\n19: a fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\n20: be allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code\n21: paths that need the row to exist (per-agent tuning, audit attribution)\n22: should call ``get_or_create_agent`` explicitly — the soft-pass here\n23: applies only to the gate decision.\n24: \"\"\"\n25: \n26: from __future__ import annotations\n27: \n28: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n29: \n30: from core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n31: \n32: # Keep the prefix in one place so ``parse_trust_error`` and ``require_trust``\n33: # can't drift if someone edits one. ``str.removeprefix`` is a no-op when the\n34: # prefix isn't present, so parse_trust_error stays robust against future\n35: # error strings that happen not to start with it.\n36: _MCP_ERROR_PREFIX = \"Error (403): \"\n37: \n38: \n39: async def require_trust(\n40:     db: AsyncSession,\n41:     tenant_id: str,\n42:     agent_id: str,\n43:     min_level: int,\n44: ) -> tuple[int, bool, str | None]:\n45:     \"\"\"Look up the agent's trust level and gate on ``min_level``.\n46: \n47:     Returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass, ``(trust, not_found,\n48:     error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is ``True`` when no agent row\n49:     exists for ``(tenant_id, agent_id)``; in that case the effective\n50:     trust used for the gate decision is ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` (the\n51:     same level a freshly-registered agent receives). Error format\n52:     matches the wider MCP handler convention of ``\"Error (403): …\"``.\n53: \n54:     .. warning::\n55: \n56:        **Write paths MUST check ``not_found`` independently of\n57:        ``error_str``.** The soft-pass returns ``(DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n58:        True, None)`` for a missing agent when ``min_level <=\n59:        DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` — ``error_str`` is ``None`` so a caller\n60:        that only gates on ``terr`` will let an unregistered, fabricated\n61:        ``agent_id`` through. The soft-pass exists for read-only\n62:        ergonomics (``memclaw_list``, recall) where attribution is\n63:        cosmetic. On any path that persists records keyed to the caller-\n64:        supplied ``agent_id`` (memories, audit-log rows, evolve\n65:        outcomes, insights), an unregistered name corrupts the audit\n66:        trail because identity attribution becomes unverifiable.\n67: \n68:        Pattern to follow — see ``core_api/routes/evolve.py``::\n69: \n70:            _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(...)\n71:            if not_found:\n72:                raise HTTPException(\n73:                    status_code=403,\n74:                    detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered ...\",\n75:                )\n76:            if terr:\n77:                raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n78: \n79:        The same pattern is in ``routes/insights.py`` and the MCP\n80:        handlers ``memclaw_evolve`` / ``memclaw_insights`` in\n81:        ``mcp_server.py``. ``memclaw_list`` (read-only) intentionally\n82:        does NOT check ``not_found`` and is the canonical \"soft-pass\n83:        OK\" call site.\n84:     \"\"\"\n85:     from core_api.services.agent_service import lookup_agent\n86: \n87:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n88:     if agent is None:\n89:         # Soft-pass: a missing row is not a permission failure. Use the\n90:         # platform default trust so the gate matches what the agent would\n91:         # receive on its first write (when get_or_create_agent runs).\n92:         if min_level <= DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL:\n93:             return DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL, True, None\n94:         # Distinguish \"no row\" from a real ``trust_level`` denial so an\n95:         # operator debugging the 403 doesn't go looking for a row to\n96:         # upgrade that doesn't exist. The ``register the agent by\n97:         # writing one memory first`` hint matches the recovery path\n98:         # used elsewhere in the system (writes auto-create via\n99:         # ``get_or_create_agent``).\n100:         return (\n101:             DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n102:             True,\n103:             f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered \"\n104:             f\"(no row; effective trust {DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL} < required {min_level}). \"\n105:             f\"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n106:         )\n107:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(agent, dict) else getattr(agent, \"trust_level\", 0)\n108:     if trust < min_level:\n109:         return (\n110:             trust,\n111:             False,\n112:             f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n113:         )\n114:     return trust, False, None\n115: \n116: \n117: def parse_trust_error(terr: str) -> str:\n118:     \"\"\"Strip the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` from an error produced by ``require_trust``.\n119: \n120:     REST routes use this to surface the underlying reason as the detail\n121:     of an ``HTTPException`` without leaking the MCP-style prefix. Uses\n122:     ``str.removeprefix`` which is a no-op when the prefix isn't present —\n123:     keeps the helper safe against future callers that feed in arbitrary\n124:     error strings.\n125:     \"\"\"\n126:     return terr.removeprefix(_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX)\n\n(End of file - total 126 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n\nShared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\nunder ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\nreaching into each other's private symbols.\n\n``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\nfor the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\nid\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\nstring. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\nthe MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\nstrips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\nan ``HTTPException``.\n\nWhen the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\nto ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\npermission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\na fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\nbe allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement.\n\nShared by the MCP handlers in ``core_api.mcp_server`` and the REST routes\nunder ``core_api.routes`` so both surfaces gate on the same rule without\nreaching into each other's private symbols.\n\n``require_trust`` returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass and\n``(trust, not_found, error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is a typed flag\nfor the \"agent row is missing\" case so callers can distinguish \"unknown\nid\" from \"known id with insufficient trust\" without parsing the error\nstring. The error string carries the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` constant so\nthe MCP handler convention stays in one place; ``parse_trust_error``\nstrips that prefix so REST routes can surface the bare detail through\nan ``HTTPException``.\n\nWhen the agent row is missing (``not_found=True``), the gate falls back\nto ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` rather than treating the row's absence as a\npermission failure: API-key admission already proved authorization, so\na fresh agent that hasn't yet been materialised by a write must still\nbe allowed to use any tool the tenant's default policy permits. Code\npaths that need the row to exist (per-agent tuning, audit attribution)\nshould call ``get_or_create_agent`` explicitly — the soft-pass here\napplies only to the gate decision.\n\"\"\"\n\nfrom __future__ import annotations\n\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n\n# Keep the prefix in one place so ``parse_trust_error`` and ``require_trust``\n# can't drift if someone edits one. ``str.removeprefix`` is a no-op when the\n# prefix isn't present, so parse_trust_error stays robust against future\n# error strings that happen not to start with it.\n_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX = \"Error (403): \"\n\n\nasync def require_trust(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    min_level: int,\n) -> tuple[int, bool, str | None]:\n    \"\"\"Look up the agent's trust level and gate on ``min_level``.\n\n    Returns ``(trust, not_found, None)`` on pass, ``(trust, not_found,\n    error_str)`` on fail. ``not_found`` is ``True`` when no agent row\n    exists for ``(tenant_id, agent_id)``; in that case the effective\n    trust used for the gate decision is ``DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` (the\n    same level a freshly-registered agent receives). Error format\n    matches the wider MCP handler convention of ``\"Error (403): …\"``.\n\n    .. warning::\n\n       **Write paths MUST check ``not_found`` independently of\n       ``error_str``.** The soft-pass returns ``(DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n       True, None)`` for a missing agent when ``min_level <=\n       DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL`` — ``error_str`` is ``None`` so a caller\n       that only gates on ``terr`` will let an unregistered, fabricated\n       ``agent_id`` through. The soft-pass exists for read-only\n       ergonomics (``memclaw_list``, recall) where attribution is\n       cosmetic. On any path that persists records keyed to the caller-\n       supplied ``agent_id`` (memories, audit-log rows, evolve\n       outcomes, insights), an unregistered name corrupts the audit\n       trail because identity attribution becomes unverifiable.\n\n       Pattern to follow — see ``core_api/routes/evolve.py``::\n\n           _, not_found, terr = await require_trust(...)\n           if not_found:\n               raise HTTPException(\n                   status_code=403,\n                   detail=f\"Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered ...\",\n               )\n           if terr:\n               raise HTTPException(status_code=403, detail=parse_trust_error(terr))\n\n       The same pattern is in ``routes/insights.py`` and the MCP\n       handlers ``memclaw_evolve`` / ``memclaw_insights`` in\n       ``mcp_server.py``. ``memclaw_list`` (read-only) intentionally\n       does NOT check ``not_found`` and is the canonical \"soft-pass\n       OK\" call site.\n    \"\"\"\n    from core_api.services.agent_service import lookup_agent\n\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n    if agent is None:\n        # Soft-pass: a missing row is not a permission failure. Use the\n        # platform default trust so the gate matches what the agent would\n        # receive on its first write (when get_or_create_agent runs).\n        if min_level <= DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL:\n            return DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL, True, None\n        # Distinguish \"no row\" from a real ``trust_level`` denial so an\n        # operator debugging the 403 doesn't go looking for a row to\n        # upgrade that doesn't exist. The ``register the agent by\n        # writing one memory first`` hint matches the recovery path\n        # used elsewhere in the system (writes auto-create via\n        # ``get_or_create_agent``).\n        return (\n            DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL,\n            True,\n            f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' is not registered \"\n            f\"(no row; effective trust {DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL} < required {min_level}). \"\n            f\"Register the agent by writing one memory first.\",\n        )\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0) if isinstance(agent, dict) else getattr(agent, \"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < min_level:\n        return (\n            trust,\n            False,\n            f\"{_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX}Agent '{agent_id}' (trust_level={trust}) < required {min_level}.\",\n        )\n    return trust, False, None\n\n\ndef parse_trust_error(terr: str) -> str:\n    \"\"\"Strip the ``_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX`` from an error produced by ``require_trust``.\n\n    REST routes use this to surface the underlying reason as the detail\n    of an ``HTTPException`` without leaking the MCP-style prefix. Uses\n    ``str.removeprefix`` which is a no-op when the prefix isn't present —\n    keeps the helper safe against future callers that feed in arbitrary\n    error strings.\n    \"\"\"\n    return terr.removeprefix(_MCP_ERROR_PREFIX)","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":126,"totalLines":126,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/trust_service.py","time":{"start":1780729435843,"end":1780729435852}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e3c0905864be40a016a23c65bc6ac8191b6199bb558a43c57"}},"id":"prt_e9bbed6b7001SqvbeQBxKM7ySL","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbeaa50001P4eN3xa8y6ig7F"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729435856,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_ThXNoYVmQMBW0S600A2umegv","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","offset":1,"limit":180},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: \"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n2: \n3: import logging\n4: from datetime import UTC, datetime\n5: from typing import Any\n6: \n7: from fastapi import HTTPException\n8: from sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n9: \n10: from core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\n11: from core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\n12: from core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n13: \n14: logger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n15: \n16: \n17: async def get_or_create_agent(\n18:     db: AsyncSession,\n19:     tenant_id: str,\n20:     agent_id: str,\n21:     fleet_id: str | None = None,\n22:     *,\n23:     require_approval: bool = False,\n24:     display_name: str | None = None,\n25:     install_id: str | None = None,\n26: ) -> dict:\n27:     \"\"\"Return the agent dict, creating it on first encounter.\n28: \n29:     The storage API handles upsert semantics and race-condition safety.\n30: \n31:     ``display_name`` and ``install_id`` (Task 6) are accepted optionally\n32:     on every call. On creation they're persisted; on lookup of an\n33:     existing row, ``display_name`` is refreshed if the new value\n34:     differs (so a renamed machine propagates) and ``install_id`` is\n35:     backfilled when previously NULL but never overwritten — the\n36:     install identity is stable for the row's lifetime.\n37:     \"\"\"\n38:     sc = get_storage_client()\n39:     agent = await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n40:     if agent:\n41:         # Backfill fleet_id if the agent was registered without one,\n42:         # refresh display_name when it differs (hostname change), and\n43:         # stamp install_id on first contact post-plugin-upgrade.\n44:         backfill: dict = {}\n45:         if agent.get(\"fleet_id\") is None and fleet_id is not None:\n46:             backfill[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n47:         if display_name is not None and agent.get(\"display_name\") != display_name:\n48:             backfill[\"display_name\"] = display_name\n49:         if install_id is not None and agent.get(\"install_id\") is None:\n50:             backfill[\"install_id\"] = install_id\n51:         if backfill:\n52:             agent.update(backfill)\n53:             agent[\"updated_at\"] = datetime.now(UTC)\n54:             await sc.create_or_update_agent({\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"agent_id\": agent_id, **backfill})\n55:         return agent\n56: \n57:     # Legacy-main carryover: pre-Task6 plugins all defaulted to\n58:     # ``agent_id=\"main\"``, so an upgrade from those creates a brand-new\n59:     # ``main-{install_id}`` row and orphans the old \"main\" row's\n60:     # tuning state. When this is a fresh ``main-{install_id}`` create\n61:     # for a tenant/fleet that has a legacy \"main\" row, copy\n62:     # ``trust_level`` and ``search_profile`` forward so the upgraded\n63:     # plugin keeps the operator's prior calibration. Bounded scope:\n64:     #   - only triggers for ``main-{install_id}`` ids (not arbitrary\n65:     #     custom agents) so a deliberate new agent doesn't accidentally\n66:     #     inherit\n67:     #   - skipped when ``require_approval=True`` (the explicit\n68:     #     \"start at 0\" path)\n69:     #   - leaves the legacy row intact so its memories stay queryable\n70:     #     under ``agent_id=\"main\"`` for admin recovery; operators\n71:     #     decide later whether to delete or keep as archive\n72:     inherited_trust: int | None = None\n73:     inherited_search_profile: dict[str, Any] | None = None\n74:     if not require_approval and install_id is not None and agent_id == f\"main-{install_id}\":\n75:         legacy = await sc.get_agent(\"main\", tenant_id)\n76:         if legacy and (fleet_id is None or legacy.get(\"fleet_id\") == fleet_id):\n77:             inherited_trust = legacy.get(\"trust_level\")\n78:             inherited_search_profile = legacy.get(\"search_profile\")\n79:             logger.info(\n80:                 \"carrying forward legacy 'main' agent state to install-scoped id\",\n81:                 extra={\n82:                     \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n83:                     \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n84:                     \"new_agent_id\": agent_id,\n85:                     \"inherited_trust\": inherited_trust,\n86:                 },\n87:             )\n88: \n89:     initial_trust = (\n90:         inherited_trust if inherited_trust is not None else (0 if require_approval else DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL)\n91:     )\n92:     create_payload: dict[str, Any] = {\n93:         \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n94:         \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n95:         \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n96:         \"display_name\": display_name,\n97:         \"install_id\": install_id,\n98:         \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n99:     }\n100:     if inherited_search_profile is not None:\n101:         create_payload[\"search_profile\"] = inherited_search_profile\n102:     agent = await sc.create_or_update_agent(create_payload)\n103:     await log_action(\n104:         db,\n105:         tenant_id=tenant_id,\n106:         agent_id=agent_id,\n107:         action=\"agent_registered\",\n108:         resource_type=\"agent\",\n109:         resource_id=agent.get(\"id\"),\n110:         detail={\n111:             \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n112:             \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n113:             \"display_name\": display_name,\n114:             \"install_id\": install_id,\n115:             \"carried_from_legacy_main\": inherited_trust is not None,\n116:         },\n117:     )\n118:     return agent\n119: \n120: \n121: async def lookup_agent(db: AsyncSession, tenant_id: str, agent_id: str) -> dict | None:\n122:     sc = get_storage_client()\n123:     return await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n124: \n125: \n126: async def enforce_fleet_write(\n127:     db: AsyncSession,\n128:     tenant_id: str,\n129:     agent_id: str,\n130:     fleet_id: str | None,\n131: ) -> dict:\n132:     \"\"\"Enforce write permissions. Returns the agent (auto-created if new).\"\"\"\n133:     agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n134: \n135:     # Agents can always write to their home fleet (or tenant-wide if no fleet specified)\n136:     if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n137:         return agent\n138: \n139:     # Cross-fleet write requires admin (level >= 3)\n140:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n141:     if trust < 3:\n142:         raise HTTPException(\n143:             status_code=403,\n144:             detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not writable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n145:         )\n146:     return agent\n147: \n148: \n149: async def enforce_fleet_read(\n150:     db: AsyncSession,\n151:     tenant_id: str,\n152:     agent_id: str,\n153:     fleet_id: str | None,\n154: ) -> None:\n155:     \"\"\"Enforce read permissions for search/list (read-only — never creates agents).\"\"\"\n156:     agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n157: \n158:     # Unknown agent — allow the read (agent registration happens on writes)\n159:     if not agent:\n160:         return\n161: \n162:     # Reading own fleet or tenant-wide is always allowed\n163:     if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n164:         return\n165: \n166:     # Cross-fleet read requires level >= 2\n167:     trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n168:     if trust < 2:\n169:         raise HTTPException(\n170:             status_code=403,\n171:             detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not readable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n172:         )\n173: \n174: \n175: async def authorize_memory_access(\n176:     db: AsyncSession,\n177:     tenant_id: str,\n178:     caller_agent_id: str | None,\n179:     *,\n180:     visibility: str | None,\n\n(Showing lines 1-180 of 327. Use offset=181 to continue.)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nasync def get_or_create_agent(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,","truncated":true,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","text":"\"\"\"Agent trust-level enforcement for fleet-scoped access control.\"\"\"\n\nimport logging\nfrom datetime import UTC, datetime\nfrom typing import Any\n\nfrom fastapi import HTTPException\nfrom sqlalchemy.ext.asyncio import AsyncSession\n\nfrom core_api.clients.storage_client import get_storage_client\nfrom core_api.constants import DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL\nfrom core_api.services.audit_service import log_action\n\nlogger = logging.getLogger(__name__)\n\n\nasync def get_or_create_agent(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None = None,\n    *,\n    require_approval: bool = False,\n    display_name: str | None = None,\n    install_id: str | None = None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Return the agent dict, creating it on first encounter.\n\n    The storage API handles upsert semantics and race-condition safety.\n\n    ``display_name`` and ``install_id`` (Task 6) are accepted optionally\n    on every call. On creation they're persisted; on lookup of an\n    existing row, ``display_name`` is refreshed if the new value\n    differs (so a renamed machine propagates) and ``install_id`` is\n    backfilled when previously NULL but never overwritten — the\n    install identity is stable for the row's lifetime.\n    \"\"\"\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    agent = await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n    if agent:\n        # Backfill fleet_id if the agent was registered without one,\n        # refresh display_name when it differs (hostname change), and\n        # stamp install_id on first contact post-plugin-upgrade.\n        backfill: dict = {}\n        if agent.get(\"fleet_id\") is None and fleet_id is not None:\n            backfill[\"fleet_id\"] = fleet_id\n        if display_name is not None and agent.get(\"display_name\") != display_name:\n            backfill[\"display_name\"] = display_name\n        if install_id is not None and agent.get(\"install_id\") is None:\n            backfill[\"install_id\"] = install_id\n        if backfill:\n            agent.update(backfill)\n            agent[\"updated_at\"] = datetime.now(UTC)\n            await sc.create_or_update_agent({\"tenant_id\": tenant_id, \"agent_id\": agent_id, **backfill})\n        return agent\n\n    # Legacy-main carryover: pre-Task6 plugins all defaulted to\n    # ``agent_id=\"main\"``, so an upgrade from those creates a brand-new\n    # ``main-{install_id}`` row and orphans the old \"main\" row's\n    # tuning state. When this is a fresh ``main-{install_id}`` create\n    # for a tenant/fleet that has a legacy \"main\" row, copy\n    # ``trust_level`` and ``search_profile`` forward so the upgraded\n    # plugin keeps the operator's prior calibration. Bounded scope:\n    #   - only triggers for ``main-{install_id}`` ids (not arbitrary\n    #     custom agents) so a deliberate new agent doesn't accidentally\n    #     inherit\n    #   - skipped when ``require_approval=True`` (the explicit\n    #     \"start at 0\" path)\n    #   - leaves the legacy row intact so its memories stay queryable\n    #     under ``agent_id=\"main\"`` for admin recovery; operators\n    #     decide later whether to delete or keep as archive\n    inherited_trust: int | None = None\n    inherited_search_profile: dict[str, Any] | None = None\n    if not require_approval and install_id is not None and agent_id == f\"main-{install_id}\":\n        legacy = await sc.get_agent(\"main\", tenant_id)\n        if legacy and (fleet_id is None or legacy.get(\"fleet_id\") == fleet_id):\n            inherited_trust = legacy.get(\"trust_level\")\n            inherited_search_profile = legacy.get(\"search_profile\")\n            logger.info(\n                \"carrying forward legacy 'main' agent state to install-scoped id\",\n                extra={\n                    \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n                    \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n                    \"new_agent_id\": agent_id,\n                    \"inherited_trust\": inherited_trust,\n                },\n            )\n\n    initial_trust = (\n        inherited_trust if inherited_trust is not None else (0 if require_approval else DEFAULT_TRUST_LEVEL)\n    )\n    create_payload: dict[str, Any] = {\n        \"tenant_id\": tenant_id,\n        \"agent_id\": agent_id,\n        \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n        \"display_name\": display_name,\n        \"install_id\": install_id,\n        \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n    }\n    if inherited_search_profile is not None:\n        create_payload[\"search_profile\"] = inherited_search_profile\n    agent = await sc.create_or_update_agent(create_payload)\n    await log_action(\n        db,\n        tenant_id=tenant_id,\n        agent_id=agent_id,\n        action=\"agent_registered\",\n        resource_type=\"agent\",\n        resource_id=agent.get(\"id\"),\n        detail={\n            \"fleet_id\": fleet_id,\n            \"trust_level\": initial_trust,\n            \"display_name\": display_name,\n            \"install_id\": install_id,\n            \"carried_from_legacy_main\": inherited_trust is not None,\n        },\n    )\n    return agent\n\n\nasync def lookup_agent(db: AsyncSession, tenant_id: str, agent_id: str) -> dict | None:\n    sc = get_storage_client()\n    return await sc.get_agent(agent_id, tenant_id)\n\n\nasync def enforce_fleet_write(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> dict:\n    \"\"\"Enforce write permissions. Returns the agent (auto-created if new).\"\"\"\n    agent = await get_or_create_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id, fleet_id)\n\n    # Agents can always write to their home fleet (or tenant-wide if no fleet specified)\n    if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n        return agent\n\n    # Cross-fleet write requires admin (level >= 3)\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < 3:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not writable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n        )\n    return agent\n\n\nasync def enforce_fleet_read(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    agent_id: str,\n    fleet_id: str | None,\n) -> None:\n    \"\"\"Enforce read permissions for search/list (read-only — never creates agents).\"\"\"\n    agent = await lookup_agent(db, tenant_id, agent_id)\n\n    # Unknown agent — allow the read (agent registration happens on writes)\n    if not agent:\n        return\n\n    # Reading own fleet or tenant-wide is always allowed\n    if fleet_id is None or fleet_id == agent.get(\"fleet_id\"):\n        return\n\n    # Cross-fleet read requires level >= 2\n    trust = agent.get(\"trust_level\", 0)\n    if trust < 2:\n        raise HTTPException(\n            status_code=403,\n            detail=f\"fleet-scope policy: fleet '{fleet_id}' is not readable by principals of fleet '{agent.get('fleet_id') or 'none'}'.\",\n        )\n\n\nasync def authorize_memory_access(\n    db: AsyncSession,\n    tenant_id: str,\n    caller_agent_id: str | None,\n    *,\n    visibility: str | None,","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":180,"totalLines":327,"truncated":true}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py","time":{"start":1780729435846,"end":1780729435855}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e3c0905864be40a016a23c65bc6b0819193765d92b2fcf65f"}},"id":"prt_e9bbed6c5001XuAUeDVDuNGxXI","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbeaa50001P4eN3xa8y6ig7F"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729435872,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"grep","callID":"call_nvR0C474S6GW53LHQbRk3Uvc","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"pattern":"suppression|trust_level|scope_agent|scope_team|scope_org|visibility|tenant isolation|Full audit","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main","include":"*.md"},"output":"Found 49 matches\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/README.md:\n  Line 254: - **Visibility scopes** — every memory is stamped at write time: `scope_agent` (private), `scope_team` (fleet-wide, default), or `scope_org` (cross-fleet). Cross-fleet recall is permissioned, not open\n\n  Line 256: - **Full audit log** — every write, delete, and transition logged with tenant and scope context\n\n  Line 291: > Single-agent benchmarks can't measure cross-agent recall, outcome propagation between agents, fleet-scoped visibility, or governance-aware retrieval. Those are the questions that decide whether a memory system is *deployable* inside a company. See [`docs/performance.md`](docs/performance.md#what-these-benchmarks-cant-measure).\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/api-surfaces.md:\n  Line 37: | Redistribute (mass reassign) | REST only | Destructive bulk op requires `trust_level >= 3`. Admin operation, not agent-driven. |\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/docs/integration-without-plugin.md:\n  Line 158: The default `trust_level=1` lets the agent write to its home fleet. Elevate when you need cross-fleet writes, keystone authoring, or deletes:\n\n  Line 164:   -d '{\"trust_level\": 2}'\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:\n  Line 18:   gates `scope_agent` privacy. Resolved by your runtime. Never fabricate,\n\n  Line 21:   `visibility=scope_team`, for fleet-scoped reads, and for cross-fleet\n\n  Line 27: or write privately (`visibility=scope_agent`) until resolved.\n\n  Line 67: ## Sharing: visibility and scope\n\n  Line 69: **Visibility (on write):** `scope_agent` (private) · `scope_team`\n\n  Line 70: *(default — your fleet)* · `scope_org` (all fleets in tenant).\n\n  Line 75: Prefer `scope_team` when writing; prefer `scope=agent` when reading\n\n  Line 157: **`memclaw_write(content=? | items=?, fleet_id=?, visibility=\"scope_team\", memory_type=?, weight=?, metadata=?, write_mode=\"auto\", source_uri=?, run_id=?)`**\n\n  Line 170: which bypasses `scope_team` enforcement for teammates filtering by\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/CHANGELOG.md:\n  Line 18: * **core:** OSS suppression mirror + boundary guard (CAURA-694) ([#244](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/244)) ([64cf3e4](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/64cf3e446cf26b634e3dee39197f2fcc76affe88))\n\n  Line 196: * **fleet-stats:** include agent trust_level in per-agent records ([#116](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/116)) ([1c0e6e7](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/1c0e6e75d8f3cd8e624a0ec1c225cb50c4cc488b))\n\n  Line 313: * **api:** include visibility in GET /memories/{memory_id} response ([#40](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/40)) ([9562a79](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/9562a799411264e71d64d5669a196486d46bbc5b))\n\n  Line 318: * **contradiction:** scope candidate fetch by writer visibility ([#38](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/38)) ([6e31348](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/6e31348203377af2b6a54418c4149371604c312d))\n\n  Line 324: * **memories:** apply visibility scoping to memory count endpoints (CAURA-000) ([#42](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/42)) ([6e26dcb](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/6e26dcb360d5dcce91877f59a6aaf7fe4e4cd9c6))\n\n  Line 327: * **memory:** drop unused unscoped indexes ix_memories_status + ix_memories_visibility (CAURA-629) ([#35](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/35)) ([9b2e071](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/9b2e07111d38d7f9b3d6e1a50102658e986a73c1))\n\n  Line 328: * **memory:** restore ix_memories_status + ix_memories_visibility (CAURA-632) ([#45](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/issues/45)) ([4be9017](https://github.com/caura-ai/caura-memclaw/commit/4be90175ebb520b6752d6b23642b3e05b92a2c10))\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/static/docs/integration-guide.md:\n  Line 37: | `memclaw_write` | Yes | Yes | Single or batch write. Send `content` for one memory, or `items` (≤100) for a batch — the batch path batches embeddings and parallelizes enrichment. LLM auto-infers type, weight, status, title, summary, tags, temporal dates, PII flags. Contradiction detection auto-marks conflicting memories. `visibility` = `scope_agent` / `scope_team` (default) / `scope_org`. Content >2,000 chars is auto-chunked |\n\n  Line 38: | `memclaw_recall` | Yes | Yes | Hybrid semantic + keyword search with graph-enhanced retrieval (expands through entity relations up to 2 hops). `include_brief=true` returns an LLM-summarized context paragraph instead of raw results. Supports `fleet_ids` for multi-fleet queries. Respects visibility. Default `top_k=5`, max 20 |\n\n  Line 176: | Visibility | Passed per-call (`scope_agent` / `scope_team` / `scope_org`) | Passed per-call (`scope_agent` / `scope_team` / `scope_org`) |\n\n  Line 353: | `/api/v1/agents/{agent_id}/trust?tenant_id=` | PATCH | Update trust level (body: `{\"trust_level\": 2}`) |\n\n  Line 392: - Set visibility: \"scope_agent\" (you only), \"scope_team\" (default), \"scope_org\" (all fleets)\n\n  Line 411: - Default visibility is \"scope_team\" — shared within your fleet\n\n  Line 412: - Set visibility: \"scope_org\" to share across all fleets in the organization\n\n  Line 413: - Set visibility: \"scope_agent\" for agent-only notes\n\n  Line 445:     \"visibility\": \"scope_org\"\n\n  Line 450: LLM enrichment auto-classifies as `fact`, weight `0.9`, title \"Customer X: PostgreSQL 16 on GKE\", tags `[\"customer-x\", \"postgresql\", \"gke\"]`. Entity extraction identifies \"Customer X\" (org), \"PostgreSQL 16\" (technology), \"GKE\" (technology). Visibility `scope_org` means all fleets can see this.\n\n  Line 622: ### Memory visibility\n\n  Line 624: Controls who can see a memory. Set on write via `visibility` field.\n\n  Line 628: | `scope_agent` | Only the creating agent | Personal notes, drafts, scratch work |\n\n  Line 629: | `scope_team` | All agents in the same fleet (default) | Team-scoped knowledge |\n\n  Line 630: | `scope_org` | All agents across all fleets | Company-wide facts, cross-team decisions |\n\n  Line 632: Search respects visibility automatically. Agents see: all `scope_org` memories + `scope_team` memories in their fleet + their own `scope_agent` memories. Admin API key sees all except `scope_agent`.\n\n  Line 640: - Both parent and children inherit type, weight, status, visibility\n\n\n/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/external/caura-memclaw-main/plugin/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:\n  Line 19:   gates `scope_agent` privacy. Resolved by your runtime. Never fabricate,\n\n  Line 22:   `visibility=scope_team`, for fleet-scoped reads, and for cross-fleet\n\n  Line 28: or write privately (`visibility=scope_agent`) until resolved.\n\n  Line 66: ## Sharing: visibility and scope\n\n  Line 68: **Visibility (on write):** `scope_agent` (private) · `scope_team`\n\n  Line 69: *(default — your fleet)* · `scope_org` (all fleets in tenant).\n\n  Line 74: Prefer `scope_team` when writing; prefer `scope=agent` when reading\n\n  Line 144: - NEVER write with org-wide visibility (`scope_org`) unless the memory\n\n  Line 183: **Operational visibility**: rolling skip counters\n\n  Line 248: **`memclaw_write(content=? | items=?, visibility=\"scope_team\", memory_type=?, weight=?, metadata=?, write_mode=\"auto\", source_uri=?, run_id=?)`**\n","metadata":{"matches":49,"truncated":false},"title":"suppression|trust_level|scope_agent|scope_team|scope_org|visibility|tenant isolation|Full audit","time":{"start":1780729435854,"end":1780729435871}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_0e3c0905864be40a016a23c65bc6b88191a87bd358a2b979ac"}},"id":"prt_e9bbed6c7001x5bli7S9EbhqMu","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbeaa50001P4eN3xa8y6ig7F"}}
