spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/prompts/iteration-083.md","metadata":{"count":8,"truncated":false},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings","time":{"start":1780729459944,"end":1780729459964}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_093f04617cdaf9f7016a23c673a3648191863047b0851c5381"}},"id":"prt_e9bbf33b9001TXldHeKuTNAn7d","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbed8f00017iv2Bh2k6Bm4EF"}}
{"type":"step_finish","timestamp":1780729460271,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbf362d001HO8nI5VlbyKIP7","reason":"tool-calls","snapshot":"cf2d86c31d023953ec6b63c47df79021127f0e4f","messageID":"msg_e9bbed8f00017iv2Bh2k6Bm4EF","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","type":"step-finish","tokens":{"total":100813,"input":8078,"output":135,"reasoning":952,"cache":{"write":0,"read":91648}},"cost":0}}
{"type":"step_start","timestamp":1780729462357,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"id":"prt_e9bbf3e50001SWRQvnM3gmSu8t","messageID":"msg_e9bbf3730001MPEHYq3GzPYOet","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","snapshot":"105fbc4e51fb15a7d9b80244760ee520c8521de1","type":"step-start"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729469399,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_5gugm5Zf8NLY8qXwgTTaMvDu","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-083.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-083.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 083 — governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 129486 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: MemClaw’s governance is built for fleet deployment, not a personal local store. The public contract states the product is “multi-tenant, multi-agent” and “built for fleets, not single agents,” with scoped memory, cross-agent propagation, and fleet-wide trust tiers as core architecture (`README.md:30`, `README.md:36`).\n9: \n10: Scope model: every memory row has `tenant_id`, optional `fleet_id`, `agent_id`, and `visibility`; visibility defaults to `scope_team` (`common/models/memory.py:19`, `common/models/memory.py:20`, `common/models/memory.py:21`, `common/models/memory.py:61`, `common/models/memory.py:64`). Constants define the three visibility scopes: `scope_agent`, `scope_team`, `scope_org` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:97`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:105`). The agent-facing skill states the write-time meanings: `scope_agent` private, `scope_team` default fleet, `scope_org` all fleets in tenant (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:67`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`).\n11: \n12: Tenant and cross-tenant enforcement: auth stores the current tenant and optional readable tenants in context vars, then sets Postgres GUCs `app.tenant_id` and `app.readable_tenant_ids` for RLS-aware deployments (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:33`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:74`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:79`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`). MCP auth similarly resolves `X-Tenant-ID`, verified `X-Agent-ID`, readable tenants, and capabilities into request context (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:145`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:165`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:206`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:213`).\n13: \n14: Read filtering is default-deny for private agent memories: list/search returns `scope_org` and `scope_team`, plus `scope_agent` only when the caller owns it; otherwise `scope_agent` is excluded (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:114`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:140`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). Search applies the same visibility filter and fleet filter, with `scope_org` allowed to escape explicit fleet scoping (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:445`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:450`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:454`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:459`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:465`).\n15: \n16: Trust tiers: MemClaw has four agent trust levels: `restricted`, `standard`, `cross_fleet`, `admin`, defaulting to `1` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:538`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:539`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:545`). The public guide maps them to capabilities: `0` read-only, `1` home-fleet write, `2` cross-fleet read, `3` cross-fleet write/delete/update-others (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:168`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:169`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:170`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`). Service gates enforce this: cross-fleet write requires trust >=3, cross-fleet read requires trust >=2, delete requires trust >=3, and by-id access reuses `scope_agent` ownership plus fleet trust ladder (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:149`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:185`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:201`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:204`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:250`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). MCP recall narrows low-trust agents without explicit fleet filters back to their own fleet, then applies `enforce_fleet_read` for explicit fleet reads (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:512`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:516`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:521`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:523`).\n17: \n18: Suppression: enterprise org soft-delete emits `memclaw.org.suppression-changed`; the event carries tenant IDs plus action `suppress` or `restore` (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:1`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:40`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:41`). The handler writes each affected tenant into a suppression mirror and re-raises partial failures so Pub/Sub redelivers rather than leaving an authz hole (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:14`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:15`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:85`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`). Core API checks suppression on authenticated requests and returns 403 with a generic suspended message (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:283`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). The suppression cache intentionally fails open on storage errors to avoid self-DOS (`core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:118`).\n19: \n20: PII quarantine: the README claims PII is “auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries” (`README.md:253`). In the capped code pass, I found the detection and metadata/reporting surface: enrichment schema has `contains_pii` and `pii_types` (`common/enrichment/schema.py:106`, `common/enrichment/schema.py:107`), memory creation writes those into metadata (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:631`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:634`), and stats count PII-tagged memories (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:924`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). I did not see quarantine enforcement code in the files read.\n21: \n22: Audit logging: MemClaw has a generic `audit_log` model with `tenant_id`, optional `agent_id`, `action`, `resource_type`, `resource_id`, JSON detail, and timestamp (`common/models/audit.py:11`, `common/models/audit.py:17`, `common/models/audit.py:18`, `common/models/audit.py:19`, `common/models/audit.py:20`, `common/models/audit.py:22`, `common/models/audit.py:23`). `log_action` builds the audit payload and queues it when the audit queue is active (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:32`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:58`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:63`). Cross-tenant reads emit one audit event per source tenant, logged to the source tenant for forensic visibility (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:71`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:103`). Settings have a separate append-only per-change audit trail with `changed_by` and flat diffs (`common/models/organization_settings.py:36`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:37`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:49`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:51`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`).\n23: \n24: ## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory\n25: 1. **Claim** · ADAPT trust tiers into provenance trust, not access-control trust. **Evidence** · MemClaw trust levels gate fleet powers (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`) and enforcement lives in fleet read/write/delete gates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `provenance-trust-weighting-for-derived-memory`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-importing authz semantics would add fake multi-agent complexity to a single-user store. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The transferable concept is “not all memories deserve equal authority.” Spec Kit already has importance tiers and constitutional always-surface memories; the missing analog is trust weighting for source/provenance, e.g. human-authored > validated automated > shadow-derived > stale/low-confidence.\n26: \n27: 2. **Claim** · ADAPT append-only audit for automated memory mutations. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s settings path writes a flat diff audit row after updates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`), and generic audit events include tenant, agent, action, resource, and detail (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:56`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `automated-mutation-audit-trail`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full fleet audit queue is unnecessary and can become operational noise. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user Spec Kit does not need forensic tenant accounting, but it does need explainability for self-maintaining index changes, shadow feedback promotions, tier changes, bulk deletes, retention sweeps, and causal-edge backfills.\n28: \n29: 3. **Claim** · REJECT agent/fleet/cross-tenant scope machinery; keep only a local default-deny analog for sensitive auto-derived state. **Evidence** · MemClaw scopes are explicitly fleet concepts (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:72`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:73`), and query filters prevent `scope_agent` leaks across callers (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). **Maps-to** · 027 child or new sub-packet: `local-visibility-for-ephemeral-derived-state`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · If copied directly, Spec Kit would gain meaningless “agents/fleets” and confuse retrieval policy. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · There is no cross-team leak risk in a local single-user database. The only useful analog is default-deny surfacing for draft, shadow, quarantined, or low-confidence derived memories until promoted.\n30: \n31: 4. **Claim** · DEFER PII quarantine; adopt only lightweight sensitive-content tagging if there is a concrete local need. **Evidence** · README claims PII quarantine before crossing fleet boundaries (`README.md:253`), while visible code in this pass shows PII detection metadata and counts (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet if pursued: `local-sensitive-memory-tagging`. **Verdict** · DEFER. **Risk** · PII quarantine can become false-positive friction in a personal/local store; it solves cross-fleet exposure, which Spec Kit lacks. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The concept of marking sensitive generated memories may transfer for operator awareness or export hygiene, but quarantine-as-is is a fleet boundary mechanism.\n32: \n33: 5. **Claim** · REJECT suppression as org lifecycle enforcement; ADAPT “suppression” only as a local disabled/archived memory state. **Evidence** · Suppression mirrors enterprise soft-delete events into tenant rows (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`) and blocks authenticated requests for suppressed tenants (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). **Maps-to** · existing Spec Kit retention/archive surfaces or new sub-packet: `memory-suppression-state-for-retrieval`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · Importing tenant suppression would create dead configuration and fake security posture. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · A single-user local store needs no org soft-delete boundary. It may benefit from explicit suppression flags for “do not retrieve this memory” without deleting evidence.\n34: \n35: ## Negative knowledge\n36: Multi-tenant RLS context, `tenant_id` GUCs, and readable-tenant GUCs do not transfer directly; they exist to isolate tenants and widen reads only for authorized cross-tenant credentials (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`).\n37: \n38: Agent-scoped credentials, gateway-injected `X-Agent-ID`, `X-Readable-Tenant-IDs`, `X-Capabilities`, and gateway shared-secret perimeter checks are fleet ingress machinery, not local-memory needs (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:210`; `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:385`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:395`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:401`).\n39: \n40: Fleet read/write ladders should not be ported as authorization. Trust >=2 for cross-fleet read and trust >=3 for cross-fleet write/delete are meaningful only when multiple fleets and agents share a tenant (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`).\n41: \n42: Per-tenant concurrency bulkheads and rate limiting are noisy-neighbor controls. Spec Kit’s local SQLite/vector store has different bottlenecks and no tenant starvation problem (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:4`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:150`; `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py:8`).\n43: \n44: Org suppression eventing, tenant-suppression mirrors, Pub/Sub redelivery, DLQ behavior, and fail-open suppression cache are enterprise lifecycle controls. They do not map to a single-user local memory system except as a simple retrieval-suppressed state (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`; `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`).\n45: \n46: Cross-tenant read audit should not transfer as-is. Spec Kit can audit automated changes, but it does not need “who read from my tenant” forensic rows (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`).\n47: \n48: PII quarantine before cross-fleet exposure is mostly negative knowledge for Spec Kit. If local export/sync features later appear, sensitive tagging may become relevant; until then, quarantine is solving a fleet leak boundary (`README.md:253`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`).\n49: \n50: ## Open questions\n51: 1. Where, if anywhere, is MemClaw’s README-claimed PII quarantine enforced beyond metadata tagging and stats?\n52: 2. Does Spec Kit already record enough audit metadata for `memory_bulk_delete`, `memory_save`, `retention_sweep`, causal backfill, embedding reconcile, and tier updates?\n53: 3. Should Spec Kit distinguish `source_trust` from `importance_tier`, so “constitutional” importance cannot be confused with “human-verified” provenance?\n54: 4. Should shadow-first feedback reducers write an audit/event log before promotion, or is current telemetry sufficient?\n55: 5. Is a local `suppressed` or `do_not_surface` retrieval state needed, or do existing `deprecated`, `temporary`, and archive states cover it?\n56: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"083\",\"focus\":\"governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"topVerdicts\":[\"REJECT: fleet-scale tenant/fleet/cross-tenant scoping and suppression machinery\",\"ADAPT: provenance trust weighting and append-only audit for automated memory mutations\"],\"sources\":[\"README.md:253\",\"common/models/memory.py:61\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846\"]}\n\n(End of file - total 56 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 083 — governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 129486 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw’s governance is built for fleet deployment, not a personal local store. The public contract states the product is “multi-tenant, multi-agent” and “built for fleets, not single agents,” with scoped memory, cross-agent propagation, and fleet-wide trust tiers as core architecture (`README.md:30`, `README.md:36`).\n\nScope model: every memory row has `tenant_id`, optional `fleet_id`, `agent_id`, and `visibility`; visibility defaults to `scope_team` (`common/models/memory.py:19`, `common/models/memory.py:20`, `common/models/memory.py:21`, `common/models/memory.py:61`, `common/models/memory.py:64`). Constants define the three visibility scopes: `scope_agent`, `scope_team`, `scope_org` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:97`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:105`). The agent-facing skill states the write-time meanings: `scope_agent` private, `scope_team` default fleet, `scope_org` all fleets in tenant (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:67`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`).\n\nTenant and cross-tenant enforcement: auth stores the current tenant and optional readable tenants in context vars, then sets Postgres GUCs `app.tenant_id` and `app.readable_tenant_ids` for RLS-aware deployments (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:33`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:74`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:79`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`). MCP auth similarly resolves `X-Tenant-ID`, verified `X-Agent-ID`, readable tenants, and capabilities into request context (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:145`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:165`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:206`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:213`).\n\nRead filtering is default-deny for private agent memories: list/search returns `scope_org` and `scope_team`, plus `scope_agent` only when the caller owns it; otherwise `scope_agent` is excluded (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:114`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:140`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). Search applies the same visibility filter and fleet filter, with `scope_org` allowed to escape explicit fleet scoping (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:445`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:450`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:454`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:459`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:465`).\n\nTrust tiers: MemClaw has four agent trust levels: `restricted`, `standard`, `cross_fleet`, `admin`, defaulting to `1` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:538`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:539`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:545`). The public guide maps them to capabilities: `0` read-only, `1` home-fleet write, `2` cross-fleet read, `3` cross-fleet write/delete/update-others (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:168`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:169`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:170`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`). Service gates enforce this: cross-fleet write requires trust >=3, cross-fleet read requires trust >=2, delete requires trust >=3, and by-id access reuses `scope_agent` ownership plus fleet trust ladder (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:149`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:185`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:201`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:204`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:250`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). MCP recall narrows low-trust agents without explicit fleet filters back to their own fleet, then applies `enforce_fleet_read` for explicit fleet reads (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:512`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:516`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:521`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:523`).\n\nSuppression: enterprise org soft-delete emits `memclaw.org.suppression-changed`; the event carries tenant IDs plus action `suppress` or `restore` (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:1`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:40`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:41`). The handler writes each affected tenant into a suppression mirror and re-raises partial failures so Pub/Sub redelivers rather than leaving an authz hole (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:14`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:15`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:85`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`). Core API checks suppression on authenticated requests and returns 403 with a generic suspended message (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:283`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). The suppression cache intentionally fails open on storage errors to avoid self-DOS (`core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:118`).\n\nPII quarantine: the README claims PII is “auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries” (`README.md:253`). In the capped code pass, I found the detection and metadata/reporting surface: enrichment schema has `contains_pii` and `pii_types` (`common/enrichment/schema.py:106`, `common/enrichment/schema.py:107`), memory creation writes those into metadata (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:631`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:634`), and stats count PII-tagged memories (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:924`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). I did not see quarantine enforcement code in the files read.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-083.md","text":"# Iteration 083 — governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.68 · **tokens:** 129486 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw’s governance is built for fleet deployment, not a personal local store. The public contract states the product is “multi-tenant, multi-agent” and “built for fleets, not single agents,” with scoped memory, cross-agent propagation, and fleet-wide trust tiers as core architecture (`README.md:30`, `README.md:36`).\n\nScope model: every memory row has `tenant_id`, optional `fleet_id`, `agent_id`, and `visibility`; visibility defaults to `scope_team` (`common/models/memory.py:19`, `common/models/memory.py:20`, `common/models/memory.py:21`, `common/models/memory.py:61`, `common/models/memory.py:64`). Constants define the three visibility scopes: `scope_agent`, `scope_team`, `scope_org` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:97`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:105`). The agent-facing skill states the write-time meanings: `scope_agent` private, `scope_team` default fleet, `scope_org` all fleets in tenant (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:67`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`).\n\nTenant and cross-tenant enforcement: auth stores the current tenant and optional readable tenants in context vars, then sets Postgres GUCs `app.tenant_id` and `app.readable_tenant_ids` for RLS-aware deployments (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:33`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:74`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:79`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`). MCP auth similarly resolves `X-Tenant-ID`, verified `X-Agent-ID`, readable tenants, and capabilities into request context (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:145`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:165`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:206`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:213`).\n\nRead filtering is default-deny for private agent memories: list/search returns `scope_org` and `scope_team`, plus `scope_agent` only when the caller owns it; otherwise `scope_agent` is excluded (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:114`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:140`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). Search applies the same visibility filter and fleet filter, with `scope_org` allowed to escape explicit fleet scoping (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:445`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:450`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:454`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:459`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:465`).\n\nTrust tiers: MemClaw has four agent trust levels: `restricted`, `standard`, `cross_fleet`, `admin`, defaulting to `1` (`core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:538`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:539`, `core-api/src/core_api/constants.py:545`). The public guide maps them to capabilities: `0` read-only, `1` home-fleet write, `2` cross-fleet read, `3` cross-fleet write/delete/update-others (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:168`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:169`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:170`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`). Service gates enforce this: cross-fleet write requires trust >=3, cross-fleet read requires trust >=2, delete requires trust >=3, and by-id access reuses `scope_agent` ownership plus fleet trust ladder (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:149`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:185`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:201`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:204`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:250`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). MCP recall narrows low-trust agents without explicit fleet filters back to their own fleet, then applies `enforce_fleet_read` for explicit fleet reads (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:512`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:516`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:521`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:523`).\n\nSuppression: enterprise org soft-delete emits `memclaw.org.suppression-changed`; the event carries tenant IDs plus action `suppress` or `restore` (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:1`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:40`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:41`). The handler writes each affected tenant into a suppression mirror and re-raises partial failures so Pub/Sub redelivers rather than leaving an authz hole (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:14`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:15`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:85`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`). Core API checks suppression on authenticated requests and returns 403 with a generic suspended message (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:283`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). The suppression cache intentionally fails open on storage errors to avoid self-DOS (`core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:118`).\n\nPII quarantine: the README claims PII is “auto-detected and quarantined before it can cross fleet boundaries” (`README.md:253`). In the capped code pass, I found the detection and metadata/reporting surface: enrichment schema has `contains_pii` and `pii_types` (`common/enrichment/schema.py:106`, `common/enrichment/schema.py:107`), memory creation writes those into metadata (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:631`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:634`), and stats count PII-tagged memories (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:924`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). I did not see quarantine enforcement code in the files read.\n\nAudit logging: MemClaw has a generic `audit_log` model with `tenant_id`, optional `agent_id`, `action`, `resource_type`, `resource_id`, JSON detail, and timestamp (`common/models/audit.py:11`, `common/models/audit.py:17`, `common/models/audit.py:18`, `common/models/audit.py:19`, `common/models/audit.py:20`, `common/models/audit.py:22`, `common/models/audit.py:23`). `log_action` builds the audit payload and queues it when the audit queue is active (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:32`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:58`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:63`). Cross-tenant reads emit one audit event per source tenant, logged to the source tenant for forensic visibility (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:71`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:101`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:103`). Settings have a separate append-only per-change audit trail with `changed_by` and flat diffs (`common/models/organization_settings.py:36`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:37`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:49`, `common/models/organization_settings.py:51`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`).\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory\n1. **Claim** · ADAPT trust tiers into provenance trust, not access-control trust. **Evidence** · MemClaw trust levels gate fleet powers (`docs/integration-without-plugin.md:167`, `docs/integration-without-plugin.md:171`) and enforcement lives in fleet read/write/delete gates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `provenance-trust-weighting-for-derived-memory`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-importing authz semantics would add fake multi-agent complexity to a single-user store. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The transferable concept is “not all memories deserve equal authority.” Spec Kit already has importance tiers and constitutional always-surface memories; the missing analog is trust weighting for source/provenance, e.g. human-authored > validated automated > shadow-derived > stale/low-confidence.\n\n2. **Claim** · ADAPT append-only audit for automated memory mutations. **Evidence** · MemClaw’s settings path writes a flat diff audit row after updates (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:801`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:824`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846`), and generic audit events include tenant, agent, action, resource, and detail (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:50`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:56`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet: `automated-mutation-audit-trail`. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full fleet audit queue is unnecessary and can become operational noise. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user Spec Kit does not need forensic tenant accounting, but it does need explainability for self-maintaining index changes, shadow feedback promotions, tier changes, bulk deletes, retention sweeps, and causal-edge backfills.\n\n3. **Claim** · REJECT agent/fleet/cross-tenant scope machinery; keep only a local default-deny analog for sensitive auto-derived state. **Evidence** · MemClaw scopes are explicitly fleet concepts (`static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:69`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:70`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:72`, `static/skills/memclaw/SKILL.md:73`), and query filters prevent `scope_agent` leaks across callers (`core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:136`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:149`). **Maps-to** · 027 child or new sub-packet: `local-visibility-for-ephemeral-derived-state`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · If copied directly, Spec Kit would gain meaningless “agents/fleets” and confuse retrieval policy. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · There is no cross-team leak risk in a local single-user database. The only useful analog is default-deny surfacing for draft, shadow, quarantined, or low-confidence derived memories until promoted.\n\n4. **Claim** · DEFER PII quarantine; adopt only lightweight sensitive-content tagging if there is a concrete local need. **Evidence** · README claims PII quarantine before crossing fleet boundaries (`README.md:253`), while visible code in this pass shows PII detection metadata and counts (`core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:632`, `core-api/src/core_api/repositories/memory_repository.py:927`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet if pursued: `local-sensitive-memory-tagging`. **Verdict** · DEFER. **Risk** · PII quarantine can become false-positive friction in a personal/local store; it solves cross-fleet exposure, which Spec Kit lacks. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The concept of marking sensitive generated memories may transfer for operator awareness or export hygiene, but quarantine-as-is is a fleet boundary mechanism.\n\n5. **Claim** · REJECT suppression as org lifecycle enforcement; ADAPT “suppression” only as a local disabled/archived memory state. **Evidence** · Suppression mirrors enterprise soft-delete events into tenant rows (`common/events/org_suppression_event.py:3`, `common/events/org_suppression_event.py:7`) and blocks authenticated requests for suppressed tenants (`core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:267`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:282`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:285`). **Maps-to** · existing Spec Kit retention/archive surfaces or new sub-packet: `memory-suppression-state-for-retrieval`. **Verdict** · REJECT fleet mechanism / ADAPT concept. **Risk** · Importing tenant suppression would create dead configuration and fake security posture. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · A single-user local store needs no org soft-delete boundary. It may benefit from explicit suppression flags for “do not retrieve this memory” without deleting evidence.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nMulti-tenant RLS context, `tenant_id` GUCs, and readable-tenant GUCs do not transfer directly; they exist to isolate tenants and widen reads only for authorized cross-tenant credentials (`core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:29`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:52`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:70`, `core-api/src/core_api/db/session.py:84`).\n\nAgent-scoped credentials, gateway-injected `X-Agent-ID`, `X-Readable-Tenant-IDs`, `X-Capabilities`, and gateway shared-secret perimeter checks are fleet ingress machinery, not local-memory needs (`core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:189`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/mcp_server.py:210`; `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:385`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:395`, `core-api/src/core_api/auth.py:401`).\n\nFleet read/write ladders should not be ported as authorization. Trust >=2 for cross-fleet read and trust >=3 for cross-fleet write/delete are meaningful only when multiple fleets and agents share a tenant (`core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:166`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:263`).\n\nPer-tenant concurrency bulkheads and rate limiting are noisy-neighbor controls. Spec Kit’s local SQLite/vector store has different bottlenecks and no tenant starvation problem (`core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:4`, `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/per_tenant_concurrency.py:150`; `core-api/src/core_api/middleware/rate_limit.py:8`).\n\nOrg suppression eventing, tenant-suppression mirrors, Pub/Sub redelivery, DLQ behavior, and fail-open suppression cache are enterprise lifecycle controls. They do not map to a single-user local memory system except as a simple retrieval-suppressed state (`common/events/suppression_handlers.py:9`, `common/events/suppression_handlers.py:101`; `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:24`, `core-api/src/core_api/suppression.py:87`).\n\nCross-tenant read audit should not transfer as-is. Spec Kit can audit automated changes, but it does not need “who read from my tenant” forensic rows (`core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:84`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:99`).\n\nPII quarantine before cross-fleet exposure is mostly negative knowledge for Spec Kit. If local export/sync features later appear, sensitive tagging may become relevant; until then, quarantine is solving a fleet leak boundary (`README.md:253`; `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:630`).\n\n## Open questions\n1. Where, if anywhere, is MemClaw’s README-claimed PII quarantine enforced beyond metadata tagging and stats?\n2. Does Spec Kit already record enough audit metadata for `memory_bulk_delete`, `memory_save`, `retention_sweep`, causal backfill, embedding reconcile, and tier updates?\n3. Should Spec Kit distinguish `source_trust` from `importance_tier`, so “constitutional” importance cannot be confused with “human-verified” provenance?\n4. Should shadow-first feedback reducers write an audit/event log before promotion, or is current telemetry sufficient?\n5. Is a local `suppressed` or `do_not_surface` retrieval state needed, or do existing `deprecated`, `temporary`, and archive states cover it?\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"083\",\"focus\":\"governance / trust tiers / scoping / audit\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.68,\"topVerdicts\":[\"REJECT: fleet-scale tenant/fleet/cross-tenant scoping and suppression machinery\",\"ADAPT: provenance trust weighting and append-only audit for automated memory mutations\"],\"sources\":[\"README.md:253\",\"common/models/memory.py:61\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/agent_service.py:139\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/audit_service.py:81\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:846\"]}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":56,"totalLines":56,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-083.md","time":{"start":1780729469391,"end":1780729469396}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06784b55b712f96e016a23c67d55588191b03250d5bffe862e"}},"id":"prt_e9bbf59ac001ZeHwVblx9EoQue","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbf3730001MPEHYq3GzPYOet"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729469539,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_yfOL61k430KCrHtMVoG6iQ1W","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-086.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-086.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 086 — entity / relationship / graph modeling\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.78 · **tokens:** 117657 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: MemClaw models memories, entities, memory-entity links, and entity-entity relations as separate storage concepts. `Memory` has optional RDF-ish fields (`subject_entity_id`, `predicate`, `object_value`) and one memory-to-memory lifecycle pointer, `supersedes_id`; it does not expose a general memory-to-memory edge table in the inspected model. Evidence: `common/models/memory.py:44`, `common/models/memory.py:45`, `common/models/memory.py:49`, `common/models/memory.py:50`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n9: \n10: Entity graph storage is explicit but entity-centered: `entities` stores canonical entity rows, `memory_entity_links` is a composite `(memory_id, entity_id)` tagging table with a `role`, and `relations` stores directed entity-to-entity relations with `relation_type`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `common/models/entity.py:12`, `common/models/entity.py:27`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/entity.py:53`, `common/models/entity.py:56`, `common/models/entity.py:62`. The initial schema adds a natural-key uniqueness constraint on `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`, confirming relations are entity edges, not memory edges. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:135`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:143`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:157`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:162`.\n11: \n12: Extraction is LLM-first with a structured JSON schema. The prompt asks for `entities`, `relations`, and `mentions`, including canonical names, entity types, roles, relation types, and mention/coreference clusters. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:30`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:31`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:32`. The call uses a deterministic CRC32 seed and provider response schema, then validates into `ExtractedGraph`; fallback returns regex-derived entities and no relations. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:65`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:77`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:112`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:122`.\n13: \n14: Creation and validation happen in the extraction worker. It filters invalid/generic names, dedupes by canonical name, embeds entity names, resolves exact matches first and similarity matches second, preserves first-seen canonical names while storing aliases, then bulk-upserts entity rows and memory-entity links. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:22`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:105`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:127`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:172`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:200`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:253`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:294`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:326`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:341`.\n15: \n16: Relations are created only when both endpoint entities resolve; the memory becomes provenance via `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:361`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:362`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:368`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:370`. Storage makes relation writes idempotent with `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE`, refreshing weight and latest non-null evidence without wiping old evidence on null writes. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3011`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3013`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3015`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3021`.\n17: \n18: Relationships feed recall in two ways. First, entity-token queries can short-circuit into `ENTITY_LOOKUP`: entity FTS, graph expansion, memory collection through `memory_entity_links`, then scoring by hop/relationship boost instead of vector similarity. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:109`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:125`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:131`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:295`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:313`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:381`. Second, normal scored search can apply an entity/graph boost by matching query tokens to entities, expanding relation hops, collecting linked memories, and multiplying score by hop/relation weights. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2736`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2741`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2755`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2768`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2781`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2783`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1042`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1053`.\n19: \n20: MemClaw also has graph hygiene and inference machinery: cross-link discovery links under-connected memories to semantically similar entities only when text verification passes, and relation inference creates/reinforces `related_to` edges from entity co-occurrence. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:26`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:72`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:92`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:132`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:21`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:46`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:60`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:152`.\n21: \n22: ## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/004 + 027/005)\n23: 1. **Claim** · Keep causal memory edges separate from entity/relationship tags; use entities as an auxiliary recall and validation channel, not as causal truth.\n24: **Evidence** · MemClaw’s explicit relation table is entity-to-entity with `evidence_memory_id`, while memory-level linkage is `memory_entity_links` plus the special `supersedes_id` pointer. `common/models/entity.py:27`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/entity.py:53`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n25: **Maps-to** · new sub-packet.\n26: **Verdict** · ADAPT.\n27: **Risk** · Entity extraction noise can make non-causal co-mentions look important.\n28: **Confidence** · High.\n29: **Why it transfers (or not)** · Transfers well to local SQLite if treated as a side-channel; it should not contaminate Spec Kit’s 027/004 causal-edge tombstone lifecycle or 027/005 deterministic metadata-edge promoter.\n30: \n31: 2. **Claim** · Relationship creation should be evidence-backed and idempotent.\n32: **Evidence** · Extracted relations are written only when both endpoint entities resolve, and each relation carries `evidence_memory_id`; storage upserts on the relation natural key and preserves existing evidence when a new write has null evidence. `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:361`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:370`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3013`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3021`.\n33: **Maps-to** · 027/004.\n34: **Verdict** · ADAPT.\n35: **Risk** · Latest-evidence-wins may hide conflicting provenance unless Spec Kit stores evidence history.\n36: **Confidence** · High.\n37: **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit already has causal edges and tombstones; the transferable part is requiring provenance memory/spec-doc evidence and idempotent natural keys for relationship promotion.\n38: \n39: 3. **Claim** · Add deterministic guards before promoting relationship metadata.\n40: **Evidence** · MemClaw uses structured response schema plus deterministic seed for LLM extraction, filters blocklisted/too-short names, dedupes first occurrence, preserves first-seen canonical names, and stores aliases instead of allowing longer hallucinated names to become canonical. `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:112`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:22`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:200`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:253`.\n41: **Maps-to** · 027/005.\n42: **Verdict** · ADOPT.\n43: **Risk** · Over-strict canonicalization can miss useful aliases.\n44: **Confidence** · High.\n45: **Why it transfers (or not)** · Strongly transfers because 027/005 is already deterministic; use this as a pattern for validating parent/child/frontmatter entity claims before edge promotion.\n46: \n47: 4. **Claim** · Entity graph recall should be a bounded boost or explicit short-circuit, never an unbounded traversal.\n48: **Evidence** · MemClaw rejects entity-lookup when entity matches are too broad, caps expanded entities and boosted memories, scores by hop/relationship weights, and falls back to normal search if entity lookup fails. `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:82`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:90`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:286`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:322`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2787`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/parallel_embed_entity_boost.py:195`.\n49: **Maps-to** · new sub-packet.\n50: **Verdict** · ADAPT.\n51: **Risk** · In a small local store, boosts may overfit and dominate semantic/BM25 ranking.\n52: **Confidence** · Medium-high.\n53: **Why it transfers (or not)** · The bounded/fallback design transfers; the fleet-scale concurrency pieces do not. Spec Kit can use local entity overlap as an explainable recall boost alongside existing graph/degree channels.\n54: \n55: 5. **Claim** · Co-occurrence-inferred relations should be deferred unless Spec Kit can attach confidence, evidence, and tombstone semantics.\n56: **Evidence** · MemClaw infers `related_to` edges from shared `memory_entity_links`, reinforces weights by co-occurrence, and inserts without direct evidence memory. `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:21`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:46`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:60`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:110`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:123`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:152`.\n57: **Maps-to** · 027/004.\n58: **Verdict** · DEFER.\n59: **Risk** · Co-occurrence can create durable false relationships that need deletion/tombstone behavior.\n60: **Confidence** · Medium.\n61: **Why it transfers (or not)** · For single-user local memory, co-occurrence can help discovery but should not become a causal edge without explicit provenance and reversible lifecycle handling.\n62: \n63: ## Negative knowledge\n64: Do not copy tenant/fleet scoping, cross-tenant visibility widening, per-tenant storage bulkheads, or fleet purge logic. They solve MemClaw’s SaaS/fleet isolation problem, not Spec Kit’s local single-user relationship model. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:130`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:171`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:354`.\n65: \n66: Do not copy Postgres-specific graph storage machinery as-is: pgvector/HNSW, TSVECTOR/GIN triggers, LATERAL joins, and HTTP storage-client batching are implementation details for a production service. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:21`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:68`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:85`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:92`.\n67: \n68: Do not copy background fleet-worker architecture. MemClaw explicitly frames entity extraction as off-hot-path and future worker/PubSub work; Spec Kit should prefer deterministic local maintenance passes. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:67`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:72`.\n69: \n70: Do not copy automatic cross-linking without safeguards. MemClaw’s cross-linker only targets active embedded memories, under-connected rows, thresholded similar entities, and optional text verification; copying only the “link similar entity” part would create false links. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:47`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:72`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:132`.\n71: \n72: Do not treat MemClaw’s `relations` as proof it has general memory-to-memory causal edges. The inspected relation model is entity-to-entity; the inspected memory-to-memory mechanism is only `supersedes_id`. Evidence: `common/models/entity.py:35`, `common/models/entity.py:39`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n73: \n74: ## Open questions\n75: Should Spec Kit introduce a local `entities`/`memory_entity_links` auxiliary schema, or should entity signals live in existing memory metadata/frontmatter only?\n76: \n77: Can 027/005’s deterministic metadata-edge promoter also promote entity links, while keeping causal edges restricted to parent/child/parent-chain relationships?\n78: \n79: What minimum provenance should a Spec Kit entity relation require: exact frontmatter field, matching spec path hierarchy, textual co-occurrence, or LLM/heuristic extraction evidence?\n80: \n81: Should entity/relationship links participate in 027/004 tombstones, or should they have a separate invalidation lifecycle so noisy entity links do not pollute causal-edge history?\n82: \n83: Would a subject-entity preflight guard reduce false causal promotions, similar to MemClaw’s “both subject IDs present and different means skip” rule? Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:24`.\n84: \n85: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"086\",\"focus\":\"entity / relationship / graph modeling\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.78,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: separate entity relationship side-channel from causal memory edges\",\"ADOPT: deterministic validation guards before metadata-edge promotion\",\"ADAPT: bounded entity graph recall boost with fallbacks\",\"DEFER: co-occurrence inferred relations without tombstone/provenance semantics\"],\"sources\":[\"common/models/entity.py:27\",\"common/models/memory.py:80\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709\"]}\n\n(End of file - total 85 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 086 — entity / relationship / graph modeling\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.78 · **tokens:** 117657 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw models memories, entities, memory-entity links, and entity-entity relations as separate storage concepts. `Memory` has optional RDF-ish fields (`subject_entity_id`, `predicate`, `object_value`) and one memory-to-memory lifecycle pointer, `supersedes_id`; it does not expose a general memory-to-memory edge table in the inspected model. Evidence: `common/models/memory.py:44`, `common/models/memory.py:45`, `common/models/memory.py:49`, `common/models/memory.py:50`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n\nEntity graph storage is explicit but entity-centered: `entities` stores canonical entity rows, `memory_entity_links` is a composite `(memory_id, entity_id)` tagging table with a `role`, and `relations` stores directed entity-to-entity relations with `relation_type`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `common/models/entity.py:12`, `common/models/entity.py:27`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/entity.py:53`, `common/models/entity.py:56`, `common/models/entity.py:62`. The initial schema adds a natural-key uniqueness constraint on `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`, confirming relations are entity edges, not memory edges. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:135`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:143`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:157`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:162`.\n\nExtraction is LLM-first with a structured JSON schema. The prompt asks for `entities`, `relations`, and `mentions`, including canonical names, entity types, roles, relation types, and mention/coreference clusters. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:30`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:31`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:32`. The call uses a deterministic CRC32 seed and provider response schema, then validates into `ExtractedGraph`; fallback returns regex-derived entities and no relations. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:65`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:77`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:112`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:122`.\n\nCreation and validation happen in the extraction worker. It filters invalid/generic names, dedupes by canonical name, embeds entity names, resolves exact matches first and similarity matches second, preserves first-seen canonical names while storing aliases, then bulk-upserts entity rows and memory-entity links. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:22`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:105`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:127`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:172`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:200`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:253`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:294`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:326`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:341`.\n\nRelations are created only when both endpoint entities resolve; the memory becomes provenance via `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:361`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:362`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:368`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:370`. Storage makes relation writes idempotent with `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE`, refreshing weight and latest non-null evidence without wiping old evidence on null writes. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3011`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3013`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3015`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3021`.\n\nRelationships feed recall in two ways. First, entity-token queries can short-circuit into `ENTITY_LOOKUP`: entity FTS, graph expansion, memory collection through `memory_entity_links`, then scoring by hop/relationship boost instead of vector similarity. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:109`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:125`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:131`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:295`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:313`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:381`. Second, normal scored search can apply an entity/graph boost by matching query tokens to entities, expanding relation hops, collecting linked memories, and multiplying score by hop/relation weights. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2736`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2741`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2755`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2768`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2781`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2783`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1042`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1053`.\n\nMemClaw also has graph hygiene and inference machinery: cross-link discovery links under-connected memories to semantically similar entities only when text verification passes, and relation inference creates/reinforces `related_to` edges from entity co-occurrence. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:26`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:72`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:92`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:132`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:21`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:46`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:60`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:152`.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-086.md","text":"# Iteration 086 — entity / relationship / graph modeling\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.78 · **tokens:** 117657 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw models memories, entities, memory-entity links, and entity-entity relations as separate storage concepts. `Memory` has optional RDF-ish fields (`subject_entity_id`, `predicate`, `object_value`) and one memory-to-memory lifecycle pointer, `supersedes_id`; it does not expose a general memory-to-memory edge table in the inspected model. Evidence: `common/models/memory.py:44`, `common/models/memory.py:45`, `common/models/memory.py:49`, `common/models/memory.py:50`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n\nEntity graph storage is explicit but entity-centered: `entities` stores canonical entity rows, `memory_entity_links` is a composite `(memory_id, entity_id)` tagging table with a `role`, and `relations` stores directed entity-to-entity relations with `relation_type`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `common/models/entity.py:12`, `common/models/entity.py:27`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/entity.py:53`, `common/models/entity.py:56`, `common/models/entity.py:62`. The initial schema adds a natural-key uniqueness constraint on `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`, confirming relations are entity edges, not memory edges. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:135`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:143`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:157`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:162`.\n\nExtraction is LLM-first with a structured JSON schema. The prompt asks for `entities`, `relations`, and `mentions`, including canonical names, entity types, roles, relation types, and mention/coreference clusters. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:30`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:31`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:32`. The call uses a deterministic CRC32 seed and provider response schema, then validates into `ExtractedGraph`; fallback returns regex-derived entities and no relations. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:65`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:77`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:104`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:112`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:122`.\n\nCreation and validation happen in the extraction worker. It filters invalid/generic names, dedupes by canonical name, embeds entity names, resolves exact matches first and similarity matches second, preserves first-seen canonical names while storing aliases, then bulk-upserts entity rows and memory-entity links. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:22`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:105`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:127`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:172`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:200`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:253`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:294`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:326`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:341`.\n\nRelations are created only when both endpoint entities resolve; the memory becomes provenance via `evidence_memory_id`. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:361`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:362`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:368`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:370`. Storage makes relation writes idempotent with `ON CONFLICT DO UPDATE`, refreshing weight and latest non-null evidence without wiping old evidence on null writes. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3011`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3013`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3015`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3021`.\n\nRelationships feed recall in two ways. First, entity-token queries can short-circuit into `ENTITY_LOOKUP`: entity FTS, graph expansion, memory collection through `memory_entity_links`, then scoring by hop/relationship boost instead of vector similarity. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:109`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:125`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:131`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:295`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:313`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:381`. Second, normal scored search can apply an entity/graph boost by matching query tokens to entities, expanding relation hops, collecting linked memories, and multiplying score by hop/relation weights. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2736`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2741`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2755`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2768`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2781`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2783`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1042`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1053`.\n\nMemClaw also has graph hygiene and inference machinery: cross-link discovery links under-connected memories to semantically similar entities only when text verification passes, and relation inference creates/reinforces `related_to` edges from entity co-occurrence. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:26`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:72`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:92`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:132`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:21`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:46`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:60`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:152`.\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/004 + 027/005)\n1. **Claim** · Keep causal memory edges separate from entity/relationship tags; use entities as an auxiliary recall and validation channel, not as causal truth.\n**Evidence** · MemClaw’s explicit relation table is entity-to-entity with `evidence_memory_id`, while memory-level linkage is `memory_entity_links` plus the special `supersedes_id` pointer. `common/models/entity.py:27`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/entity.py:53`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n**Maps-to** · new sub-packet.\n**Verdict** · ADAPT.\n**Risk** · Entity extraction noise can make non-causal co-mentions look important.\n**Confidence** · High.\n**Why it transfers (or not)** · Transfers well to local SQLite if treated as a side-channel; it should not contaminate Spec Kit’s 027/004 causal-edge tombstone lifecycle or 027/005 deterministic metadata-edge promoter.\n\n2. **Claim** · Relationship creation should be evidence-backed and idempotent.\n**Evidence** · Extracted relations are written only when both endpoint entities resolve, and each relation carries `evidence_memory_id`; storage upserts on the relation natural key and preserves existing evidence when a new write has null evidence. `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:361`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:370`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3013`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:3021`.\n**Maps-to** · 027/004.\n**Verdict** · ADAPT.\n**Risk** · Latest-evidence-wins may hide conflicting provenance unless Spec Kit stores evidence history.\n**Confidence** · High.\n**Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit already has causal edges and tombstones; the transferable part is requiring provenance memory/spec-doc evidence and idempotent natural keys for relationship promotion.\n\n3. **Claim** · Add deterministic guards before promoting relationship metadata.\n**Evidence** · MemClaw uses structured response schema plus deterministic seed for LLM extraction, filters blocklisted/too-short names, dedupes first occurrence, preserves first-seen canonical names, and stores aliases instead of allowing longer hallucinated names to become canonical. `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:112`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:117`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:22`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:103`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:200`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:253`.\n**Maps-to** · 027/005.\n**Verdict** · ADOPT.\n**Risk** · Over-strict canonicalization can miss useful aliases.\n**Confidence** · High.\n**Why it transfers (or not)** · Strongly transfers because 027/005 is already deterministic; use this as a pattern for validating parent/child/frontmatter entity claims before edge promotion.\n\n4. **Claim** · Entity graph recall should be a bounded boost or explicit short-circuit, never an unbounded traversal.\n**Evidence** · MemClaw rejects entity-lookup when entity matches are too broad, caps expanded entities and boosted memories, scores by hop/relationship weights, and falls back to normal search if entity lookup fails. `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:82`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:90`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:143`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:286`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:322`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2787`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/parallel_embed_entity_boost.py:195`.\n**Maps-to** · new sub-packet.\n**Verdict** · ADAPT.\n**Risk** · In a small local store, boosts may overfit and dominate semantic/BM25 ranking.\n**Confidence** · Medium-high.\n**Why it transfers (or not)** · The bounded/fallback design transfers; the fleet-scale concurrency pieces do not. Spec Kit can use local entity overlap as an explainable recall boost alongside existing graph/degree channels.\n\n5. **Claim** · Co-occurrence-inferred relations should be deferred unless Spec Kit can attach confidence, evidence, and tombstone semantics.\n**Evidence** · MemClaw infers `related_to` edges from shared `memory_entity_links`, reinforces weights by co-occurrence, and inserts without direct evidence memory. `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:21`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:46`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:60`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:110`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:123`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:152`.\n**Maps-to** · 027/004.\n**Verdict** · DEFER.\n**Risk** · Co-occurrence can create durable false relationships that need deletion/tombstone behavior.\n**Confidence** · Medium.\n**Why it transfers (or not)** · For single-user local memory, co-occurrence can help discovery but should not become a causal edge without explicit provenance and reversible lifecycle handling.\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy tenant/fleet scoping, cross-tenant visibility widening, per-tenant storage bulkheads, or fleet purge logic. They solve MemClaw’s SaaS/fleet isolation problem, not Spec Kit’s local single-user relationship model. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:130`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:171`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:195`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:354`.\n\nDo not copy Postgres-specific graph storage machinery as-is: pgvector/HNSW, TSVECTOR/GIN triggers, LATERAL joins, and HTTP storage-client batching are implementation details for a production service. Evidence: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:21`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:68`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:85`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:92`.\n\nDo not copy background fleet-worker architecture. MemClaw explicitly frames entity extraction as off-hot-path and future worker/PubSub work; Spec Kit should prefer deterministic local maintenance passes. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:67`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:72`.\n\nDo not copy automatic cross-linking without safeguards. MemClaw’s cross-linker only targets active embedded memories, under-connected rows, thresholded similar entities, and optional text verification; copying only the “link similar entity” part would create false links. Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:47`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:72`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:126`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/discover_cross_links.py:132`.\n\nDo not treat MemClaw’s `relations` as proof it has general memory-to-memory causal edges. The inspected relation model is entity-to-entity; the inspected memory-to-memory mechanism is only `supersedes_id`. Evidence: `common/models/entity.py:35`, `common/models/entity.py:39`, `common/models/entity.py:43`, `common/models/memory.py:80`.\n\n## Open questions\nShould Spec Kit introduce a local `entities`/`memory_entity_links` auxiliary schema, or should entity signals live in existing memory metadata/frontmatter only?\n\nCan 027/005’s deterministic metadata-edge promoter also promote entity links, while keeping causal edges restricted to parent/child/parent-chain relationships?\n\nWhat minimum provenance should a Spec Kit entity relation require: exact frontmatter field, matching spec path hierarchy, textual co-occurrence, or LLM/heuristic extraction evidence?\n\nShould entity/relationship links participate in 027/004 tombstones, or should they have a separate invalidation lifecycle so noisy entity links do not pollute causal-edge history?\n\nWould a subject-entity preflight guard reduce false causal promotions, similar to MemClaw’s “both subject IDs present and different means skip” rule? Evidence: `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:3`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/subject_preflight.py:24`.\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"086\",\"focus\":\"entity / relationship / graph modeling\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.78,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: separate entity relationship side-channel from causal memory edges\",\"ADOPT: deterministic validation guards before metadata-edge promotion\",\"ADAPT: bounded entity graph recall boost with fallbacks\",\"DEFER: co-occurrence inferred relations without tombstone/provenance semantics\"],\"sources\":[\"common/models/entity.py:27\",\"common/models/memory.py:80\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/search/classify_query.py:99\",\"core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2709\"]}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":85,"totalLines":85,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-086.md","time":{"start":1780729469531,"end":1780729469537}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06784b55b712f96e016a23c67d5568819192d7046b18640ee9"}},"id":"prt_e9bbf59ef001R4pN3k3ryXt2J8","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbf3730001MPEHYq3GzPYOet"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729469720,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_h5U6HKT0jOC5D2PRDwInyl1u","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-087.md","offset":1,"limit":220},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-087.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 087 — lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 84068 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Mechanism\n8: MemClaw separates lifecycle into status-only archive, soft-delete grace, and later hard purge.\n9: \n10: Archive criteria are SQL predicates on live memories. `memory_archive_expired` marks active, non-deleted rows as `outdated` when `ts_valid_end < NOW()` and limits each batch to 500 (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1590`). `memory_archive_stale` marks active, non-deleted rows as `archived` when they are older than `stale_days`, have `recall_count = 0`, and `weight < max_weight` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1606`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1628`). Archive operations are idempotent because rows leave the `status = 'active'` candidate set after the first update (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1636`).\n11: \n12: Soft-delete is not a hard delete. `memory_soft_delete` sets `deleted_at = now()` and `status = \"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`). Hot-path updates reject soft-deleted rows and keep `deleted_at IS NULL` guards on update statements so later writes do not resurrect deleted rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:486`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:526`).\n13: \n14: Purge is the hard-delete phase. `memory_purge_soft_deleted` deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than `retention_days`; its docstring says this removes the memory row plus embedding, entity links, and idempotency response cache lines through FKs (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1653`). The DELETE predicate is `deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). Purge fanout targets only tenants with soft-deleted rows older than the maximum retention window, using DB clock to avoid client-clock drift (`core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:25`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:37`).\n15: \n16: Retention is a bounded policy snapshot. `LifecyclePurgeRequest` carries `retention_days`; the comments state fanout reads org settings at cron time and consumers trust that snapshot (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1`, `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`). The configured range is 1-30 days (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21`), settings validation reuses those constants (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:340`), and unresolved config defaults to 30 days (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537`).\n17: \n18: Supersession is status/link lifecycle, not deletion. `Memory` has `status` and `supersedes_id` fields (`common/models/memory.py:56`, `common/models/memory.py:79`). `memory_update_status` can set, clear, or CAS-check `supersedes_id` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:538`). Default search excludes `outdated` and `conflicted` memories while allowing explicit `status_filter` inspection (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`).\n19: \n20: Lifecycle audit is pre-published, stateful, and sticky-success. `LifecycleAudit` stores `org_id`, `action`, `triggered_by`, `started_at`, `finished_at`, `status`, `stats`, and `error_message` (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24`). The fanout path creates the audit row before publishing the event so publish failure leaves an observable `pending` row (`core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99`). Handlers move the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`, and SQL ops are described as safe under redelivery (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127`). Finalization stamps `finished_at` only for terminal states and blocks updates once status is already `success`, preserving original stats on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`).\n21: \n22: ## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/004)\n23: 1. **Claim** · Tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later. **Evidence** · MemClaw soft-delete sets `deleted_at` and `status=\"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`); hard purge only deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than retention (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Tombstones must be excluded from active reads everywhere or deleted causal edges can reappear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The multi-tenant wrapper does not transfer, but the local invariant does: every active causal-edge delete should first persist a tombstone timestamp/status, and hard-delete should be a separate retention sweep.\n24: \n25: 2. **Claim** · Lifecycle audit should be append-observable and sticky-success. **Evidence** · Audit rows start `pending` and expose terminal states (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:3`); finalization blocks overwriting `success` on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full audit table may be too heavy for SQLite unless scoped to lifecycle/tombstone sweeps. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit does not need Pub/Sub, but it benefits from local audit rows for tombstone sweeps: run id, action, cutoff, counts, status, error.\n26: \n27: 3. **Claim** · Persist the retention cutoff/parameter snapshot with the lifecycle request. **Evidence** · Purge payload carries `retention_days` as the per-org policy snapshot read at fanout time (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`); fanout resolves purge kwargs from config (`core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A changed setting mid-run will not affect the in-flight sweep, so the UI/docs must make snapshot semantics clear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user SQLite has no org fanout, but should still record the effective retention cutoff used by each sweep for reproducibility.\n28: \n29: 4. **Claim** · Idempotent lifecycle predicates should make retries harmless without special recovery code. **Evidence** · Archive only updates `status='active'` live rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`); purge only deletes already-soft-deleted rows beyond cutoff (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1679`); tenant purge explicitly documents rerun safety (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1701`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Batch limits can leave partial backlog, so audit stats must distinguish partial progress from completion. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit local sweeps can use SQLite predicates that naturally no-op after success, avoiding bespoke retry flags.\n30: \n31: 5. **Claim** · Supersession should hide stale facts by default while preserving inspectable lineage. **Evidence** · `supersedes_id` records lineage (`common/models/memory.py:79`); default search filters out `outdated` and `conflicted` rows but explicit status filtering can include them (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-filtering can hide historical rationale unless explain/debug views bypass the filter. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit’s causal graph already has supersedes semantics; MemClaw reinforces separating “not active for retrieval” from “safe to purge.”\n32: \n33: ## Negative knowledge\n34: Do not copy MemClaw’s multi-tenant fanout machinery. The cron service only POSTs a fanout endpoint while core-api enumerates orgs and publishes per-org events (`core-operations/src/core_operations/tasks.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:138`). Spec Kit is local/single-user and should use an in-process sweep, not Pub/Sub or REST fanout.\n35: \n36: Do not copy fleet scoping. MemClaw carries optional `fleet_id` through lifecycle payloads and SQL predicates (`common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:31`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1584`). Spec Kit has no fleet dimension.\n37: \n38: Do not copy per-org retention settings. MemClaw validates `lifecycle.memory_retention_days` per org (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:329`). Spec Kit should use one local retention policy unless a concrete multi-profile need appears.\n39: \n40: Do not copy distributed-scheduler dedup windows for local SQL lifecycle. MemClaw’s 23-hour dedup gate is for pipeline ops and cron double-fires (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:100`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376`). Local retention/tombstone sweeps should rely on idempotent SQL predicates plus audit, not time-window distributed dedup.\n41: \n42: Do not copy Postgres-specific partial-index assumptions directly. MemClaw uses Postgres partial indexes for live rows and purgeable rows (`common/models/memory.py:118`, `common/models/memory.py:131`). SQLite can use partial indexes too, but the exact pgvector/Postgres indexing strategy is fleet-storage machinery.\n43: \n44: ## Open questions\n45: Should Spec Kit add a compact `lifecycle_audit` table, or attach sweep audit metadata to existing memory/tombstone maintenance records?\n46: \n47: What is the exact retention period for causal-edge tombstones before hard-delete, and should it differ from expired governed memory retention?\n48: \n49: Should hard-delete sweeps be bounded by row count per run, and if so how should partial completion be represented in local audit?\n50: \n51: Which read paths currently need tombstone filters for causal edges, and is there a test proving deleted edges cannot reappear through graph traversal?\n52: \n53: Should superseded-but-not-deleted causal edges get a distinct status from tombstoned/deleted edges so lineage remains inspectable?\n54: \n55: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"087\",\"focus\":\"lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later\",\"ADAPT: sticky lifecycle audit with effective retention snapshot\",\"ADAPT: idempotent lifecycle predicates for retries\"],\"sources\":[\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315\",\"common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24\",\"core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99\"]}\n\n(End of file - total 55 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 087 — lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 84068 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw separates lifecycle into status-only archive, soft-delete grace, and later hard purge.\n\nArchive criteria are SQL predicates on live memories. `memory_archive_expired` marks active, non-deleted rows as `outdated` when `ts_valid_end < NOW()` and limits each batch to 500 (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1590`). `memory_archive_stale` marks active, non-deleted rows as `archived` when they are older than `stale_days`, have `recall_count = 0`, and `weight < max_weight` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1606`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1628`). Archive operations are idempotent because rows leave the `status = 'active'` candidate set after the first update (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1636`).\n\nSoft-delete is not a hard delete. `memory_soft_delete` sets `deleted_at = now()` and `status = \"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`). Hot-path updates reject soft-deleted rows and keep `deleted_at IS NULL` guards on update statements so later writes do not resurrect deleted rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:486`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:526`).\n\nPurge is the hard-delete phase. `memory_purge_soft_deleted` deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than `retention_days`; its docstring says this removes the memory row plus embedding, entity links, and idempotency response cache lines through FKs (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1653`). The DELETE predicate is `deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). Purge fanout targets only tenants with soft-deleted rows older than the maximum retention window, using DB clock to avoid client-clock drift (`core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:25`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:37`).\n\nRetention is a bounded policy snapshot. `LifecyclePurgeRequest` carries `retention_days`; the comments state fanout reads org settings at cron time and consumers trust that snapshot (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1`, `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`). The configured range is 1-30 days (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21`), settings validation reuses those constants (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:340`), and unresolved config defaults to 30 days (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537`).\n\nSupersession is status/link lifecycle, not deletion. `Memory` has `status` and `supersedes_id` fields (`common/models/memory.py:56`, `common/models/memory.py:79`). `memory_update_status` can set, clear, or CAS-check `supersedes_id` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:538`). Default search excludes `outdated` and `conflicted` memories while allowing explicit `status_filter` inspection (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`).\n\nLifecycle audit is pre-published, stateful, and sticky-success. `LifecycleAudit` stores `org_id`, `action`, `triggered_by`, `started_at`, `finished_at`, `status`, `stats`, and `error_message` (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24`). The fanout path creates the audit row before publishing the event so publish failure leaves an observable `pending` row (`core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99`). Handlers move the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`, and SQL ops are described as safe under redelivery (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127`). Finalization stamps `finished_at` only for terminal states and blocks updates once status is already `success`, preserving original stats on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`).","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-087.md","text":"# Iteration 087 — lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 5 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.72 · **tokens:** 84068 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Mechanism\nMemClaw separates lifecycle into status-only archive, soft-delete grace, and later hard purge.\n\nArchive criteria are SQL predicates on live memories. `memory_archive_expired` marks active, non-deleted rows as `outdated` when `ts_valid_end < NOW()` and limits each batch to 500 (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1590`). `memory_archive_stale` marks active, non-deleted rows as `archived` when they are older than `stale_days`, have `recall_count = 0`, and `weight < max_weight` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1606`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1628`). Archive operations are idempotent because rows leave the `status = 'active'` candidate set after the first update (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1636`).\n\nSoft-delete is not a hard delete. `memory_soft_delete` sets `deleted_at = now()` and `status = \"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`). Hot-path updates reject soft-deleted rows and keep `deleted_at IS NULL` guards on update statements so later writes do not resurrect deleted rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:486`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:526`).\n\nPurge is the hard-delete phase. `memory_purge_soft_deleted` deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than `retention_days`; its docstring says this removes the memory row plus embedding, entity links, and idempotency response cache lines through FKs (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1653`). The DELETE predicate is `deleted_at IS NOT NULL AND deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). Purge fanout targets only tenants with soft-deleted rows older than the maximum retention window, using DB clock to avoid client-clock drift (`core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:25`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/tenants.py:37`).\n\nRetention is a bounded policy snapshot. `LifecyclePurgeRequest` carries `retention_days`; the comments state fanout reads org settings at cron time and consumers trust that snapshot (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1`, `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`). The configured range is 1-30 days (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21`), settings validation reuses those constants (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:340`), and unresolved config defaults to 30 days (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537`).\n\nSupersession is status/link lifecycle, not deletion. `Memory` has `status` and `supersedes_id` fields (`common/models/memory.py:56`, `common/models/memory.py:79`). `memory_update_status` can set, clear, or CAS-check `supersedes_id` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:538`). Default search excludes `outdated` and `conflicted` memories while allowing explicit `status_filter` inspection (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`).\n\nLifecycle audit is pre-published, stateful, and sticky-success. `LifecycleAudit` stores `org_id`, `action`, `triggered_by`, `started_at`, `finished_at`, `status`, `stats`, and `error_message` (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24`). The fanout path creates the audit row before publishing the event so publish failure leaves an observable `pending` row (`core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99`). Handlers move the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`, and SQL ops are described as safe under redelivery (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127`). Finalization stamps `finished_at` only for terminal states and blocks updates once status is already `success`, preserving original stats on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`).\n\n## Teachings for Spec Kit Memory (027/004)\n1. **Claim** · Tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later. **Evidence** · MemClaw soft-delete sets `deleted_at` and `status=\"deleted\"` (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418`); hard purge only deletes rows whose `deleted_at` is older than retention (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1674`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Tombstones must be excluded from active reads everywhere or deleted causal edges can reappear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · The multi-tenant wrapper does not transfer, but the local invariant does: every active causal-edge delete should first persist a tombstone timestamp/status, and hard-delete should be a separate retention sweep.\n\n2. **Claim** · Lifecycle audit should be append-observable and sticky-success. **Evidence** · Audit rows start `pending` and expose terminal states (`common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:3`); finalization blocks overwriting `success` on redelivery (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4350`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A full audit table may be too heavy for SQLite unless scoped to lifecycle/tombstone sweeps. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit does not need Pub/Sub, but it benefits from local audit rows for tombstone sweeps: run id, action, cutoff, counts, status, error.\n\n3. **Claim** · Persist the retention cutoff/parameter snapshot with the lifecycle request. **Evidence** · Purge payload carries `retention_days` as the per-org policy snapshot read at fanout time (`common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:4`); fanout resolves purge kwargs from config (`core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · A changed setting mid-run will not affect the in-flight sweep, so the UI/docs must make snapshot semantics clear. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Single-user SQLite has no org fanout, but should still record the effective retention cutoff used by each sweep for reproducibility.\n\n4. **Claim** · Idempotent lifecycle predicates should make retries harmless without special recovery code. **Evidence** · Archive only updates `status='active'` live rows (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1596`); purge only deletes already-soft-deleted rows beyond cutoff (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1679`); tenant purge explicitly documents rerun safety (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1701`). **Maps-to** · 027/004. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Batch limits can leave partial backlog, so audit stats must distinguish partial progress from completion. **Confidence** · High. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit local sweeps can use SQLite predicates that naturally no-op after success, avoiding bespoke retry flags.\n\n5. **Claim** · Supersession should hide stale facts by default while preserving inspectable lineage. **Evidence** · `supersedes_id` records lineage (`common/models/memory.py:79`); default search filters out `outdated` and `conflicted` rows but explicit status filtering can include them (`core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1149`). **Maps-to** · new sub-packet. **Verdict** · ADAPT. **Risk** · Over-filtering can hide historical rationale unless explain/debug views bypass the filter. **Confidence** · Medium. **Why it transfers (or not)** · Spec Kit’s causal graph already has supersedes semantics; MemClaw reinforces separating “not active for retrieval” from “safe to purge.”\n\n## Negative knowledge\nDo not copy MemClaw’s multi-tenant fanout machinery. The cron service only POSTs a fanout endpoint while core-api enumerates orgs and publishes per-org events (`core-operations/src/core_operations/tasks.py:1`, `core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:138`). Spec Kit is local/single-user and should use an in-process sweep, not Pub/Sub or REST fanout.\n\nDo not copy fleet scoping. MemClaw carries optional `fleet_id` through lifecycle payloads and SQL predicates (`common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:31`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1584`). Spec Kit has no fleet dimension.\n\nDo not copy per-org retention settings. MemClaw validates `lifecycle.memory_retention_days` per org (`core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:329`). Spec Kit should use one local retention policy unless a concrete multi-profile need appears.\n\nDo not copy distributed-scheduler dedup windows for local SQL lifecycle. MemClaw’s 23-hour dedup gate is for pipeline ops and cron double-fires (`common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:100`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376`). Local retention/tombstone sweeps should rely on idempotent SQL predicates plus audit, not time-window distributed dedup.\n\nDo not copy Postgres-specific partial-index assumptions directly. MemClaw uses Postgres partial indexes for live rows and purgeable rows (`common/models/memory.py:118`, `common/models/memory.py:131`). SQLite can use partial indexes too, but the exact pgvector/Postgres indexing strategy is fleet-storage machinery.\n\n## Open questions\nShould Spec Kit add a compact `lifecycle_audit` table, or attach sweep audit metadata to existing memory/tombstone maintenance records?\n\nWhat is the exact retention period for causal-edge tombstones before hard-delete, and should it differ from expired governed memory retention?\n\nShould hard-delete sweeps be bounded by row count per run, and if so how should partial completion be represented in local audit?\n\nWhich read paths currently need tombstone filters for causal edges, and is there a test proving deleted edges cannot reappear through graph traversal?\n\nShould superseded-but-not-deleted causal edges get a distinct status from tombstoned/deleted edges so lineage remains inspectable?\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"087\",\"focus\":\"lifecycle / retention / archive / purge / tombstones\",\"findingsCount\":5,\"newInfoRatio\":0.72,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: tombstone/grace first, hard-delete later\",\"ADAPT: sticky lifecycle audit with effective retention snapshot\",\"ADAPT: idempotent lifecycle predicates for retries\"],\"sources\":[\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1575\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315\",\"common/models/lifecycle_audit.py:24\",\"core-api/src/core_api/routes/lifecycle.py:99\"]}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":55,"totalLines":55,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-087.md","time":{"start":1780729469713,"end":1780729469718}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06784b55b712f96e016a23c67d55708191bc44a417db62c7df"}},"id":"prt_e9bbf5abb001Qkm21vAAdA03GT","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbf3730001MPEHYq3GzPYOet"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1780729469976,"sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_o1N6Iu17XAUFQGrQPX1QAjJg","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-096.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-096.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # Iteration 096 — DEEP relationship + lifecycle/tombstone -> 027/004+005 design\n2: \n3: **Status:** insight · **Findings:** 10 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 97955 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n4: \n5: ---\n6: \n7: ## Verified mechanism (deep)\n8: MemClaw soft-deletes memories by setting both `deleted_at` and `status='deleted'`: `common/models/memory.py:40-41`, `common/models/memory.py:56-59`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Hard-delete is a later purge of rows with `deleted_at IS NOT NULL` and `deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646-1687`.\n9: \n10: Grace is policy-driven, not embedded in each row. Retention is carried on purge messages as a snapshot: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1-8`, default/range is 1-30 days: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21-28`, org setting defaults to 30: `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537-546`, and fanout resolves the per-org value into publisher kwargs: `core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227-236`.\n11: \n12: Important correction to 087: the purge path is idempotent, but the soft-delete primitive is not strictly idempotent. Repeating `memory_soft_delete` rewrites `deleted_at = datetime.now(UTC)`, which can extend the grace window: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Public delete first checks tenant visibility via `get_memory_for_tenant`, which excludes already-deleted rows: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2214-2220`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:254-264`; direct storage delete still returns ok without guarding existing tombstones: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1068-1071`.\n13: \n14: Lifecycle audit is stronger than row tombstoning. A `pending` audit row is created before publishing each per-org lifecycle event: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4283-4305`; the payload carries `audit_id`, `org_id`, `triggered_by`, and optional `fleet_id`: `common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:16-31`. Consumers update the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127-139`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:204-246`. Success is sticky, so redelivery cannot downgrade or overwrite success counts: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315-4374`. Pipeline jobs also have a recent-success dedup gate over `org_id + action + finished_at`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:157-202`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376-4403`.\n15: \n16: Supersession is memory-level, not relation-table-level. `Memory.supersedes_id` points from newer memory to older memory: `common/models/memory.py:79-83`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1-6`. Contradiction handling marks the older row `outdated` or `conflicted` and wires the newer row back to the older one: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:327-368`. It avoids overwriting existing supersession edges with application guards and storage CAS: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:376-397`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1020-1037`. Retraction clears the edge with `expected_supersedes_id` CAS and treats stale-chain failures as non-owned: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1283-1298`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:973-1011`.\n17: \n18: Relations are a separate entity graph side-channel, confirming 086. `Relation` has `from_entity_id`, `relation_type`, `to_entity_id`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`, but no `deleted_at`, lifecycle state, or provenance/source enum: `common/models/entity.py:27-50`. The initial schema adds a natural unique key over `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:145-166`. Relation upsert refreshes `weight` and preserves latest non-null `evidence_memory_id`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983-3048`.\n19: \n20: Relationship provenance is limited. Extracted LLM relations get `evidence_memory_id=memory_id`: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356-373`; inferred co-occurrence `related_to` relations are inserted without evidence or provenance columns: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147-164`. Public relation schemas expose only `evidence_memory_id`, not `source_kind` or `generated_by`: `core-api/src/core_api/schemas.py:361-368`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/schemas.py:94-103`.\n21: \n22: Relationship validation exists mostly as shape/type validation, not semantic validation. LLM extraction asks for JSON with `relations` and instantiates `ExtractedGraph` via a response schema: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15-33`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:104-122`. `RelationUpsert` validates UUIDs and `weight` range only: `core-api/src/core_api/schemas.py:361-368`. Co-occurrence inference validates by thresholding shared memories and filtering live memories: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:35-74`. This confirms 086’s caution: deterministic validation guards are needed before promoting metadata edges; MemClaw does not provide a complete provenance/validation pattern to copy.\n23: \n24: ## Concrete Spec-Kit-native adoption sketch (027/004 + 027/005)\n25: 027/004 causal-edge tombstone lifecycle for SQLite:\n26: \n27: Add minimal state to causal edges, or a sidecar table if altering hot rows is risky. Preferred columns on `causal_edges`: `edge_state TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(edge_state IN ('active','tombstoned'))`, `tombstoned_at TEXT NULL`, `tombstone_reason TEXT NULL`, `tombstoned_by TEXT NULL`, `tombstone_run_id TEXT NULL`, `purge_after TEXT NULL`, `source_kind TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'manual'`, `source_ref TEXT NULL`, `source_hash TEXT NULL`. Keep a `causal_edge_tombstones` append-only audit table keyed by `edge_id` or by the natural edge key if hard-delete removes the row.\n28: \n29: Algorithm: every active causal-edge delete path must run one transaction. First `UPDATE causal_edges SET edge_state='tombstoned', tombstoned_at=COALESCE(tombstoned_at, :now), tombstone_reason=COALESCE(tombstone_reason, :reason), tombstoned_by=COALESCE(tombstoned_by, :actor), tombstone_run_id=COALESCE(tombstone_run_id, :run_id), purge_after=COALESCE(purge_after, :purge_after) WHERE edge_id IN (...) AND edge_state='active'`. Then `INSERT OR IGNORE` into `causal_edge_tombstones` with the same first-tombstone snapshot. Only after that may a purge job `DELETE FROM causal_edges WHERE edge_state='tombstoned' AND purge_after <= :now`.\n30: \n31: Idempotent re-run: repeated tombstone calls do not rewrite the first tombstone timestamp or extend grace. Repeated purge deletes zero rows after the first successful hard-delete. This intentionally improves on MemClaw’s `memory_soft_delete`, which rewrites `deleted_at` on direct repeat.\n32: \n33: 027/005 deterministic metadata-edge promotion guard:\n34: \n35: “Validated” means all of these pass before inserting a causal edge: relation type is in an allowlist such as `parent`, `child`, `parent_chain`, `phase_child`; source frontmatter parsed successfully; source and target IDs resolve to existing Spec Kit memory/spec records; no self-edge; parent-chain edges do not create a cycle; target status is not deleted/tombstoned; relation source is deterministic frontmatter or graph metadata, not inferred co-occurrence; the source document hash matches the parsed relation snapshot used for promotion.\n36: \n37: Provenance should be explicit: `source_kind='metadata_promoter'`, `generated_by='metadata-edge-promoter'`, `source_ref='<spec-or-memory-id>#frontmatter.<field>'`, `source_hash=<frontmatter hash>`, `promoter_version=<version>`. Manual causal links keep `source_kind='manual'`.\n38: \n39: Duplicate prevention: enforce a natural active-edge key like `(from_id, to_id, edge_type)` for active causal edges. On promotion, if an active manual edge with the same natural key exists, skip promotion and record `skipped_reason='manual_edge_exists'`; never add a generated duplicate. If an active generated edge from the promoter exists, update only `source_hash`, `last_validated_at`, and confidence/status metadata. If a tombstoned generated edge exists and the same validated metadata relation reappears, create a new active edge only if policy allows resurrection, and link it to the prior tombstone audit row.\n40: \n41: ## Verdict table\n42: | Claim | Maps-to | Verdict | Risk | Confidence |\n43: |---|---|---|---|---|\n44: | Use tombstone-before-hard-delete for causal edges | 027/004 | ADOPT, but preserve first tombstone timestamp instead of MemClaw’s repeat-delete rewrite | Re-running delete could extend retention if implemented like MemClaw | High |\n45: | Grace window should be policy-driven and snapshotted at purge/fanout time | 027/004 | ADAPT | SQLite local single-user does not need org fanout, but deterministic retention config still helps | High |\n46: | Sticky audit/dedup records make lifecycle retries observable and safe | 027/004 | ADOPT | Overbuilding Pub/Sub-style audit for local SQLite would be unnecessary; use compact append-only tombstone audit | High |\n47: | Supersession as a directional newer-to-older pointer is useful | New | ADAPT | 027/004/005 are edge lifecycle/promotion tasks, not contradiction resolution | Medium |\n48: | Entity relations are side-channel edges, not causal memory edges | 027/005 | ADOPT as a boundary | Accidentally promoting co-occurrence/entity edges into causal edges would pollute causal graph | High |\n49: | Relation natural-key upsert prevents duplicate generated edges | 027/005 | ADOPT | Must also avoid duplicating manual links, not just duplicate generated links | High |\n50: | Evidence-memory provenance is enough | 027/005 | REJECT | It cannot distinguish manual vs promoter vs co-occurrence generated relations | High |\n51: | LLM/schema validation is enough before promotion | 027/005 | REJECT | Shape validation does not prove a deterministic parent/child relation | High |\n52: | Co-occurrence-inferred `related_to` relations should be promoted | 027/005 | DEFER/REJECT for causal edges | No provenance, no tombstone semantics, and weak semantic validation | High |\n53: | Fleet/org lifecycle machinery should be ported to Spec Kit Memory | New | REJECT | Local SQLite does not need multi-tenant fanout, Pub/Sub, or per-org policy layers | High |\n54: \n55: ## Negative knowledge (confirmed)\n56: Do not port MemClaw’s multi-tenant/fleet lifecycle fanout. It exists because core-operations posts action fanouts and core-api publishes per-org messages: `core-operations/src/core_operations/tasks.py:24-85`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227-236`. Spec Kit Memory is local SQLite and should use a single local transaction plus local audit rows.\n57: \n58: Do not port Pub/Sub redelivery machinery. MemClaw’s handlers are designed around event redelivery, DLQ, and per-delivery audit transitions: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127-139`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:217-246`. Spec Kit needs idempotent local reruns, not distributed consumer semantics.\n59: \n60: Do not port fleet scoping or org hard-purge tables. MemClaw has tenant/fleet hard-purge table lists and explicitly preserves lifecycle audit for org deletion observability: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:162-193`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:195-223`. Spec Kit should scope by local memory/spec IDs.\n61: \n62: Do not port co-occurrence-inferred `related_to` as causal truth. It is created from shared memory links above a threshold and lacks `evidence_memory_id` on insert: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:35-74`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147-164`.\n63: \n64: DELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"096\",\"focus\":\"DEEP relationship + lifecycle/tombstone -> 027/004+005 design\",\"findingsCount\":10,\"newInfoRatio\":0.64,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: tombstone/grace/audit lifecycle, but make soft-delete first-timestamp idempotent for SQLite causal edges\",\"ADOPT: natural-key generated-edge promotion with explicit provenance and manual-edge skip guard\"],\"sources\":[\"common/models/memory.py:40\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4283\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315\",\"common/models/entity.py:27\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147\"]}\n\n(End of file - total 64 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# Iteration 096 — DEEP relationship + lifecycle/tombstone -> 027/004+005 design\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 10 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 97955 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Verified mechanism (deep)\nMemClaw soft-deletes memories by setting both `deleted_at` and `status='deleted'`: `common/models/memory.py:40-41`, `common/models/memory.py:56-59`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Hard-delete is a later purge of rows with `deleted_at IS NOT NULL` and `deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646-1687`.\n\nGrace is policy-driven, not embedded in each row. Retention is carried on purge messages as a snapshot: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1-8`, default/range is 1-30 days: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21-28`, org setting defaults to 30: `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537-546`, and fanout resolves the per-org value into publisher kwargs: `core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227-236`.\n\nImportant correction to 087: the purge path is idempotent, but the soft-delete primitive is not strictly idempotent. Repeating `memory_soft_delete` rewrites `deleted_at = datetime.now(UTC)`, which can extend the grace window: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Public delete first checks tenant visibility via `get_memory_for_tenant`, which excludes already-deleted rows: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2214-2220`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:254-264`; direct storage delete still returns ok without guarding existing tombstones: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1068-1071`.\n\nLifecycle audit is stronger than row tombstoning. A `pending` audit row is created before publishing each per-org lifecycle event: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4283-4305`; the payload carries `audit_id`, `org_id`, `triggered_by`, and optional `fleet_id`: `common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:16-31`. Consumers update the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127-139`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:204-246`. Success is sticky, so redelivery cannot downgrade or overwrite success counts: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315-4374`. Pipeline jobs also have a recent-success dedup gate over `org_id + action + finished_at`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:157-202`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376-4403`.\n\nSupersession is memory-level, not relation-table-level. `Memory.supersedes_id` points from newer memory to older memory: `common/models/memory.py:79-83`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1-6`. Contradiction handling marks the older row `outdated` or `conflicted` and wires the newer row back to the older one: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:327-368`. It avoids overwriting existing supersession edges with application guards and storage CAS: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:376-397`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1020-1037`. Retraction clears the edge with `expected_supersedes_id` CAS and treats stale-chain failures as non-owned: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1283-1298`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:973-1011`.\n\nRelations are a separate entity graph side-channel, confirming 086. `Relation` has `from_entity_id`, `relation_type`, `to_entity_id`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`, but no `deleted_at`, lifecycle state, or provenance/source enum: `common/models/entity.py:27-50`. The initial schema adds a natural unique key over `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:145-166`. Relation upsert refreshes `weight` and preserves latest non-null `evidence_memory_id`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983-3048`.\n\nRelationship provenance is limited. Extracted LLM relations get `evidence_memory_id=memory_id`: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356-373`; inferred co-occurrence `related_to` relations are inserted without evidence or provenance columns: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147-164`. Public relation schemas expose only `evidence_memory_id`, not `source_kind` or `generated_by`: `core-api/src/core_api/schemas.py:361-368`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/schemas.py:94-103`.","truncated":false,"loaded":[],"display":{"type":"file","path":"/Users/michelkerkmeester/MEGA/Development/Code_Environment/Public/.opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-096.md","text":"# Iteration 096 — DEEP relationship + lifecycle/tombstone -> 027/004+005 design\n\n**Status:** insight · **Findings:** 10 · **newInfoRatio:** 0.64 · **tokens:** 97955 · **exit:** 0 · executor: cli-opencode openai/gpt-5.5-fast(high)\n\n---\n\n## Verified mechanism (deep)\nMemClaw soft-deletes memories by setting both `deleted_at` and `status='deleted'`: `common/models/memory.py:40-41`, `common/models/memory.py:56-59`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Hard-delete is a later purge of rows with `deleted_at IS NOT NULL` and `deleted_at < NOW() - INTERVAL '1 day' * :retention_days`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646-1687`.\n\nGrace is policy-driven, not embedded in each row. Retention is carried on purge messages as a snapshot: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:1-8`, default/range is 1-30 days: `common/events/lifecycle_purge_request.py:21-28`, org setting defaults to 30: `core-api/src/core_api/services/organization_settings.py:537-546`, and fanout resolves the per-org value into publisher kwargs: `core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227-236`.\n\nImportant correction to 087: the purge path is idempotent, but the soft-delete primitive is not strictly idempotent. Repeating `memory_soft_delete` rewrites `deleted_at = datetime.now(UTC)`, which can extend the grace window: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418-423`. Public delete first checks tenant visibility via `get_memory_for_tenant`, which excludes already-deleted rows: `core-api/src/core_api/services/memory_service.py:2214-2220`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:254-264`; direct storage delete still returns ok without guarding existing tombstones: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1068-1071`.\n\nLifecycle audit is stronger than row tombstoning. A `pending` audit row is created before publishing each per-org lifecycle event: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4283-4305`; the payload carries `audit_id`, `org_id`, `triggered_by`, and optional `fleet_id`: `common/events/lifecycle_archive_request.py:16-31`. Consumers update the same audit row through `in_progress`, `success`, or `failure`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127-139`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:204-246`. Success is sticky, so redelivery cannot downgrade or overwrite success counts: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315-4374`. Pipeline jobs also have a recent-success dedup gate over `org_id + action + finished_at`: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:157-202`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4376-4403`.\n\nSupersession is memory-level, not relation-table-level. `Memory.supersedes_id` points from newer memory to older memory: `common/models/memory.py:79-83`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1-6`. Contradiction handling marks the older row `outdated` or `conflicted` and wires the newer row back to the older one: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:327-368`. It avoids overwriting existing supersession edges with application guards and storage CAS: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:376-397`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:1020-1037`. Retraction clears the edge with `expected_supersedes_id` CAS and treats stale-chain failures as non-owned: `core-api/src/core_api/services/contradiction_detector.py:1283-1298`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/routers/memories.py:973-1011`.\n\nRelations are a separate entity graph side-channel, confirming 086. `Relation` has `from_entity_id`, `relation_type`, `to_entity_id`, `weight`, and optional `evidence_memory_id`, but no `deleted_at`, lifecycle state, or provenance/source enum: `common/models/entity.py:27-50`. The initial schema adds a natural unique key over `(tenant_id, from_entity_id, relation_type, to_entity_id)`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/database/migrations/versions/001_initial_schema.py:145-166`. Relation upsert refreshes `weight` and preserves latest non-null `evidence_memory_id`: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983-3048`.\n\nRelationship provenance is limited. Extracted LLM relations get `evidence_memory_id=memory_id`: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction_worker.py:356-373`; inferred co-occurrence `related_to` relations are inserted without evidence or provenance columns: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147-164`. Public relation schemas expose only `evidence_memory_id`, not `source_kind` or `generated_by`: `core-api/src/core_api/schemas.py:361-368`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/schemas.py:94-103`.\n\nRelationship validation exists mostly as shape/type validation, not semantic validation. LLM extraction asks for JSON with `relations` and instantiates `ExtractedGraph` via a response schema: `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:15-33`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/entity_extraction.py:104-122`. `RelationUpsert` validates UUIDs and `weight` range only: `core-api/src/core_api/schemas.py:361-368`. Co-occurrence inference validates by thresholding shared memories and filtering live memories: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:35-74`. This confirms 086’s caution: deterministic validation guards are needed before promoting metadata edges; MemClaw does not provide a complete provenance/validation pattern to copy.\n\n## Concrete Spec-Kit-native adoption sketch (027/004 + 027/005)\n027/004 causal-edge tombstone lifecycle for SQLite:\n\nAdd minimal state to causal edges, or a sidecar table if altering hot rows is risky. Preferred columns on `causal_edges`: `edge_state TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'active' CHECK(edge_state IN ('active','tombstoned'))`, `tombstoned_at TEXT NULL`, `tombstone_reason TEXT NULL`, `tombstoned_by TEXT NULL`, `tombstone_run_id TEXT NULL`, `purge_after TEXT NULL`, `source_kind TEXT NOT NULL DEFAULT 'manual'`, `source_ref TEXT NULL`, `source_hash TEXT NULL`. Keep a `causal_edge_tombstones` append-only audit table keyed by `edge_id` or by the natural edge key if hard-delete removes the row.\n\nAlgorithm: every active causal-edge delete path must run one transaction. First `UPDATE causal_edges SET edge_state='tombstoned', tombstoned_at=COALESCE(tombstoned_at, :now), tombstone_reason=COALESCE(tombstone_reason, :reason), tombstoned_by=COALESCE(tombstoned_by, :actor), tombstone_run_id=COALESCE(tombstone_run_id, :run_id), purge_after=COALESCE(purge_after, :purge_after) WHERE edge_id IN (...) AND edge_state='active'`. Then `INSERT OR IGNORE` into `causal_edge_tombstones` with the same first-tombstone snapshot. Only after that may a purge job `DELETE FROM causal_edges WHERE edge_state='tombstoned' AND purge_after <= :now`.\n\nIdempotent re-run: repeated tombstone calls do not rewrite the first tombstone timestamp or extend grace. Repeated purge deletes zero rows after the first successful hard-delete. This intentionally improves on MemClaw’s `memory_soft_delete`, which rewrites `deleted_at` on direct repeat.\n\n027/005 deterministic metadata-edge promotion guard:\n\n“Validated” means all of these pass before inserting a causal edge: relation type is in an allowlist such as `parent`, `child`, `parent_chain`, `phase_child`; source frontmatter parsed successfully; source and target IDs resolve to existing Spec Kit memory/spec records; no self-edge; parent-chain edges do not create a cycle; target status is not deleted/tombstoned; relation source is deterministic frontmatter or graph metadata, not inferred co-occurrence; the source document hash matches the parsed relation snapshot used for promotion.\n\nProvenance should be explicit: `source_kind='metadata_promoter'`, `generated_by='metadata-edge-promoter'`, `source_ref='<spec-or-memory-id>#frontmatter.<field>'`, `source_hash=<frontmatter hash>`, `promoter_version=<version>`. Manual causal links keep `source_kind='manual'`.\n\nDuplicate prevention: enforce a natural active-edge key like `(from_id, to_id, edge_type)` for active causal edges. On promotion, if an active manual edge with the same natural key exists, skip promotion and record `skipped_reason='manual_edge_exists'`; never add a generated duplicate. If an active generated edge from the promoter exists, update only `source_hash`, `last_validated_at`, and confidence/status metadata. If a tombstoned generated edge exists and the same validated metadata relation reappears, create a new active edge only if policy allows resurrection, and link it to the prior tombstone audit row.\n\n## Verdict table\n| Claim | Maps-to | Verdict | Risk | Confidence |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| Use tombstone-before-hard-delete for causal edges | 027/004 | ADOPT, but preserve first tombstone timestamp instead of MemClaw’s repeat-delete rewrite | Re-running delete could extend retention if implemented like MemClaw | High |\n| Grace window should be policy-driven and snapshotted at purge/fanout time | 027/004 | ADAPT | SQLite local single-user does not need org fanout, but deterministic retention config still helps | High |\n| Sticky audit/dedup records make lifecycle retries observable and safe | 027/004 | ADOPT | Overbuilding Pub/Sub-style audit for local SQLite would be unnecessary; use compact append-only tombstone audit | High |\n| Supersession as a directional newer-to-older pointer is useful | New | ADAPT | 027/004/005 are edge lifecycle/promotion tasks, not contradiction resolution | Medium |\n| Entity relations are side-channel edges, not causal memory edges | 027/005 | ADOPT as a boundary | Accidentally promoting co-occurrence/entity edges into causal edges would pollute causal graph | High |\n| Relation natural-key upsert prevents duplicate generated edges | 027/005 | ADOPT | Must also avoid duplicating manual links, not just duplicate generated links | High |\n| Evidence-memory provenance is enough | 027/005 | REJECT | It cannot distinguish manual vs promoter vs co-occurrence generated relations | High |\n| LLM/schema validation is enough before promotion | 027/005 | REJECT | Shape validation does not prove a deterministic parent/child relation | High |\n| Co-occurrence-inferred `related_to` relations should be promoted | 027/005 | DEFER/REJECT for causal edges | No provenance, no tombstone semantics, and weak semantic validation | High |\n| Fleet/org lifecycle machinery should be ported to Spec Kit Memory | New | REJECT | Local SQLite does not need multi-tenant fanout, Pub/Sub, or per-org policy layers | High |\n\n## Negative knowledge (confirmed)\nDo not port MemClaw’s multi-tenant/fleet lifecycle fanout. It exists because core-operations posts action fanouts and core-api publishes per-org messages: `core-operations/src/core_operations/tasks.py:24-85`, `core-api/src/core_api/services/lifecycle_audit.py:227-236`. Spec Kit Memory is local SQLite and should use a single local transaction plus local audit rows.\n\nDo not port Pub/Sub redelivery machinery. MemClaw’s handlers are designed around event redelivery, DLQ, and per-delivery audit transitions: `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:127-139`, `common/events/lifecycle_handlers.py:217-246`. Spec Kit needs idempotent local reruns, not distributed consumer semantics.\n\nDo not port fleet scoping or org hard-purge tables. MemClaw has tenant/fleet hard-purge table lists and explicitly preserves lifecycle audit for org deletion observability: `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:162-193`, `core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:195-223`. Spec Kit should scope by local memory/spec IDs.\n\nDo not port co-occurrence-inferred `related_to` as causal truth. It is created from shared memory links above a threshold and lacks `evidence_memory_id` on insert: `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:35-74`, `core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147-164`.\n\nDELTA_JSON: {\"iteration\":\"096\",\"focus\":\"DEEP relationship + lifecycle/tombstone -> 027/004+005 design\",\"findingsCount\":10,\"newInfoRatio\":0.64,\"topVerdicts\":[\"ADAPT: tombstone/grace/audit lifecycle, but make soft-delete first-timestamp idempotent for SQLite causal edges\",\"ADOPT: natural-key generated-edge promotion with explicit provenance and manual-edge skip guard\"],\"sources\":[\"common/models/memory.py:40\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:418\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:1646\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4283\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:4315\",\"common/models/entity.py:27\",\"core-storage-api/src/core_storage_api/services/postgres_service.py:2983\",\"core-api/src/core_api/pipeline/steps/entity_linking/infer_relations.py:147\"]}","lineStart":1,"lineEnd":64,"totalLines":64,"truncated":false}},"title":".opencode/specs/system-spec-kit/027-xce-research-based-refinement/research/008-caura-memclaw-fleet-memory-teachings/iterations/iteration-096.md","time":{"start":1780729469970,"end":1780729469975}},"metadata":{"openai":{"itemId":"fc_06784b55b712f96e016a23c67d55788191881c3397ba09bc57"}},"id":"prt_e9bbf5b35001QYXQPfJJOUD5pw","sessionID":"ses_164436567ffeteXLf4I1Mx29cA","messageID":"msg_e9bbf3730001MPEHYq3GzPYOet"}}
